-more-confirmed-for-lego-batman-3.aspx |archive-date=October 12, 2014 |access-date=October 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Arrowverse}}\n{{Green Arrow}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen, Oliver (Arrow)}}\n[[Category:Arrow (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:The Flash (2014 TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Legends of Tomorrow characters]]\n[[Category:Supergirl (TV series) characters]]\n[[Category:Green Arrow in other media]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Marc Guggenheim]]\n[[Category:Crossover characters in television]]\n[[Category:DC Comics martial artists]]\n[[Category:DC Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:DC Comics television characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional American secret agents]]\n[[Category:Fictional archers]]\n[[Category:Fictional business executives]]\n[[Category:Fictional castaways]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2012]]\n[[Category:Fictional eskrimadors]]\n[[Category:Fictional ghosts]]\n[[Category:Fictional inmates in American federal prisons]]\n[[Category:Fictional kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Fictional mayors]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional outlaws]]\n[[Category:Fictional socialites]]\n[[Category:Fictional stalking victims]]\n[[Category:Fictional torturers]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional Wing Chun practitioners]]\n", "name_user": "Maxcardun", "label": "safe", "comment": "Black Lightning's Earth doesn't have an official designation.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliver_Queen_(Arrowverse)"}
{"title_page": "Jesse McReynolds", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Jesse McReynolds\n| image               = Jesse McReynolds.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Jesse McReynolds at the Grand Ole Opry in 2007.\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Jesse Lester McReynolds \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = Mandolin Man\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1929|07|09}}\n| birth_place         = \n| origin              = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]]\n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1947\u2013present\n| label               = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], Opryland, CMH, [[Rounder Records|Rounder]], Old Dominion, Rural Rhythm Records [[Rural Rhythm Records]]\n| associated_acts     = Jim & Jesse<br />Jesse McReynolds & The Virginia Boys\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.jimandjesse.com/}}\n}}\n'''Jesse Lester McReynolds''' (born July 9, 1929) is an American [[bluegrass music]]ian. He is best known for his innovative [[crosspicking]] and split-string styles of [[mandolin]] playing.\n\n==Biography==\nMcReynolds was born in [[Coeburn, Virginia]]. He and his brother Jim begin performing together<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p643/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Jim & Jesse|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|author2=Vinopal, David |publisher=[[All Media Guide|AMG]]|accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> in or around 1947. They originally performed under the name, \"The McReynolds Brothers.\"<ref name=\"Statman\">{{cite book | title=Bluegrass Masters: Jesse McReynolds | last=Statman|first=Andy|publisher=Oak}}</ref> In 1951, Jesse and Jim, joined by Larry Roll on guitar, made their first recording, ten gospel songs for Kentucky Records under the name \"The Virginia Trio\".<ref name=\"Statman\" /> In 1952, Jim and Jesse signed with Capitol Records, who asked them to change their name from the \"McReynolds Brothers,\" so they started recording under the name \"[[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys.\".<ref name=\"Statman\" /> They recorded 20 songs for Capitol over three sessions in 1952, 1953, and 1955.<ref name=\"Statman\" /> During this time (1952-1954), Jesse also served in the US Army in Korea (they recorded sessions in 1953 while he was on leave).<ref name=\"Statman\" /> While serving in Korea, he and [[Charlie Louvin]] of the [[Louvin Brothers]] (who was also serving in Korea) formed a band called the \"Dusty Roads Boys\" and played regular concerts for other troops.<ref>{{cite book | title=Satan is Real: The Ballad of the Louvin Brothers | last=Louvin |first = Charlie |author2=Whitmer, Benjamin  |publisher=Igniter}}</ref> After Jesse's return from Korea, [[Jim and Jesse]] continued to perform and release albums until Jim's death from cancer in 2002. McReynolds is married to his wife, Joy.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ellen|last=Harvey|title=Owners Hope to Sing Praises of Their 2YO|date=July 19, 2010|url =http://harnesslink.com/News/Owners-hope-to-sing-praises-of-their-2yo-82207|work = Harness Racing Communications|accessdate =March 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nSince 2002, Jesse has continued to perform and record as a solo artist. McReynolds plays between 60 and 70 shows each year. Jim and Jesse became [[List of Grand Ole Opry Members|members of the Grand Ole Opry]] in 1964; Jesse continues to maintain the duo's [[Grand Ole Opry|Opry]] membership since Jim's death in 2001. He became the oldest standing Opry member in March of 2020, following the death of fellow Opry member [[Jan Howard]]. In 2019, he celebrated his 55th anniversary as a member of the Opry. In January 2017 he appeared on the CMT network show Nashville as a blind singer who inspires the character [[Rayna Jaymes]] (played by [[Connie Britton]]).\n\n==Honors==\n* Member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] since 1964 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opry.com/artist/jesse-mcreynolds|accessdate=July 25, 2015|title=Jesse McReynolds|date=2013-12-06}}</ref>\n* Inducted into [[International Bluegrass Music Hall of Honor]] in 1993\n* Awarded [[National Heritage Fellowship Award]] in 1997\n* ''Bending the Rules'' nominated for \"Best Instrumental Recording of the Year\" from the [[International Bluegrass Music Association]] in 2005.\n\n==Recordings<ref name=\"Statman\"/><ref>Recordings after 1979 from Old Dominion Masters liner notes</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Album(s) !! Group !! Notes\n|-\n| 1951 || The Virginia Trio 1951: Their Early Gospel Recordings (Old Dominion, 2000); ''Sacred Songs of The Virginia Trio'' (Ultrasonic) || ''The Virginia Trio'' or ''James and Jesse McReynolds with Larry Roll'' || Ten songs originally recorded as singles for the Kentucky label, later released as a single album by Ultrasonic and Old Dominion.\n|-\n| 1952,1954,1955 || ''20 Great Songs by Jim and Jesse'' (Capitol, 1968); ''First Sounds: The Capitol Years'' (2002);<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/First-Sounds-Capitol-Jim-Jesse/dp/B00006LI54/ref=sr_1_9?ie=UTF8&qid=1437856258&sr=8-9&keywords=jim+and+jesse|accessdate= July 25, 2015}}</ref> ''Jim and Jesse: 1952-1955'' (Bear Family, 1992); ''Jim and Jesse: Best of the Early Years'' (Cleopatra, 2009) || [[Jim and Jesse]] || The duo recorded 20 songs for Capitol in three sessions. These songs have been released under various album names (not all albums listed include all 20 songs).\n|-\n| 1958 || ''Best of the Best: Legendary Bluegrass Duets''<ref>Statman reports these Starday recording sessions but does not report an album name, as it had not been released at the time of Statman's writing. The album info comes from www.jimandjesse.com and amazon.com</ref> (Federal, 2003) || [[Jim and Jesse]] || 14 singles recorded for Starday and released on various compilations but not released together until 2003 (and even then, only 10 of the tracks appear on the album)\n|-\n| 1960 || ''Bluegrass Special/Bluegrass Classics'' (2-LP set - Epic, 1963) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys || \n|-\n| 1962 || ''Radio Shows'' (2-LP set - Old Dominion, 1979) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys || Recordings of several of Jim and Jesse's radio shows on WBAM (syndicated by Martha White)\n|-\n| 1963 || ''Country Music & Bluegrass at Newport'' (Vanguard, 1963) || Various artists || Live recording from 1963 Newport Folk Festival; four tracks from Jim and Jesse\n|-\n| unknown (1960-1964)<ref>while the date of this and several other of the Epic sessions is unknown, they are listed here in chronological order as reported by Jesse to Andy Statman for his book</ref> || ''The Old Country Church'' (Epic, 1964) ||[[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys || \n|-\n| unknown (1960-1965) || ''Y'all Come! Bluegrass Humor with Jim & Jesse & the Virginia Boys'' (Epic, 1965) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys || Not to be confused with ''Y'all Come: The Essential Jim and Jesse'', a greatest hits album released later\n|- \n| unknown (1960-1965) || ''Berry Pickin' In the Country (The Great Chuck Berry Songbook)'' (Epic, 1965) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys || A cover album of Chuck Berry songs\n|-\n| unknown (1960-1966) || ''Sing Unto Him a New Song'' (Epic, 1966) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys ||\n|-\n| unknown (1960-1967) || ''Diesel on My Tail'' (Epic, 1967) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1968 || ''The All-Time Great Country Instrumentals'' (Epic, 1968) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1968-9<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jimandjesse.com/jesseContinuesOn.php | title=jimandjesse.com|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref> || ''Soft Parade'' (Elektra, 1969) || [[The Doors]] || Jesse plays mandolin on this Doors album\n|-\n| 1969 || ''Saluting the Louvin Brothers'' (Epic, 1969) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|- \n| 1969 || ''We Like Trains'' (Epic, 1969) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1971 || ''Freight Train'' (Capitol, 1971) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1972 || ''The Jim & Jesse Show'' (Prize, 1972; Old Dominion 1972) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1972 || ''Mandolin Workshop'' (Hilltop, 1972) || Jesse McReynolds ||\n|-\n| 1973 || ''Superior Sounds of Bluegrass'' (Old Dominion, 1973) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys ||\n|-\n| 1973 || ''Me and My Fiddles'' (Old Dominion, 1973) || Jesse McReynolds ||\n|-\n| 1973 || ''Bean Blossom'' (MCA, 1973) || Various Artists || Live recording of the 7th Annual Bean Blossom Bluegrass Festival; includes five tracks from Jim and Jesse\n|-\n| 1974<ref>Statman reports this as having been recorded in 1975. The liner notes of \"The Old Dominion Masters\" reports 1974</ref> || ''Jesus is the Key to the Kingdom'' (Old Dominion, 1975) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys ||\n|-\n| 1975 || ''The Jim & Jesse Show - Live in Japan''<ref name = \"ODMasters\">Liner notes for \"Old Dominion Masters,\" 4 album set released by Old Dominion and Pinecastle Records in 1999.</ref> (2-LP set - Old Dominion, 1975) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1976<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Songs About Our Country'' (Old Dominion, 1976) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1976 || ''Allen Shelton - Shelton Special'' (Rounder, 1977) || Allen Shelton || Jesse plays backup for this solo album by Allen Shelton, long time banjo player in the Virginia Boys\n|-\n| 1977<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Palace of Songs'' (Old Dominion, 1977) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1979<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Songs of Inspiration'' (Old Dominion, 1979) || [[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys ||\n|-\n| 1981<ref>Bill Monroe: The Life and Music of the Blue Grass Man by Tom Ewing</ref> || ''Master of Bluegrass'' (MCA Records, 1981) || [[Bill Monroe]] || Jesse played on two of the tracks on this album, \"Melissa's Waltz for J.B.\" and \"Lady of the Blue Ridge\"\n|-\n| 1983<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Homeland Harmony'' (Old Dominion, 1983) || [[Jim and Jesse]] ||\n|-\n| 1986<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Somewhere My Love'' (Old Dominion, 1986) || Jesse McReynolds || This was a solo effort by Jesse playing both mandolin and lead guitar, with a backup band that did not include Jim\n|-\n| 1990 <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Masters-Eddie-Adcock/dp/B0000010RT/ref=ntt_mus_dp_dpt_1 | title=amazon.com|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>|| ''The Masters'' (CMH Records, 1995) || The Masters  || One of two albums released by the bluegrass super group The Masters (Josh Graves, Kenny Baker, Eddie Adcock, Jesse McReynolds) that toured together in the late 80s and early 90s\n|-\n| 1990 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/saturday-night-fish-fry-mw0000309950 | title=allmusic.com|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>|| ''Saturday Night Fish Fry'' (CMH Records, 1995) || The Masters  ||\n|-\n| 1993<ref name=\"ODMasters\"/> || ''Honor the King of Country Music, Roy Acuff'' (Old Dominion, 1993) || [[Jim and Jesse]] || This album is sometimes referred to as \"Tribute to Roy Acuff\"\n|-\n| 2001<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/masters-of-the-mandolin-mw0000004917 |accessdate=November 10, 2018|title=Masters of the Mandolin - Bobby Osborne, Jesse McReynolds &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits}}</ref> || ''Masters of the Mandolin || Bobby Osborne and Jesse McReynolds ||\n|-\n| 2010<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jimandjesse.com/resources/JessestributetoGarciaandHunter.php | title=jimandjesse.com|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref> || ''Songs of the Grateful Dead: A Tribute to Jerry Garcia and Robert Hunter || Jesse McReynolds and Friends ||\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.jimandjesse.com/}}\n*[https://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/jesse-mcreynolds-0 Interview with Jesse McReynolds for the NAMM (National Association of Music Merchants) Oral History Program] July 23, 2011\n{{Grand Ole Opry members}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McReynolds, Jesse}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American bluegrass mandolinists]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Grand Ole Opry members]]\n[[Category:People from Coeburn, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Singers from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Jesse McReynolds\n| image               = Jesse McReynolds.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Jesse McReynolds at the Grand Ole Opry in 2007.\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Jesse Lester McReynolds \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = Mandolin Man\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1929|07|09}}\n| birth_place         = \n| origin              = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]]\n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1947\u2013present\n| label               = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], Opryland, CMH, [[Rounder Records|Rounder]], Old Dominion, Rural Rhythm Records [[Rural Rhythm Records]]\n| associated_acts     = Jim & Jesse<br />Jesse McReynolds & The Virginia Boys\n| website             = {{URL|http://www.jimandjesse.com/}}\n}}\n'''Jesse Lester McReynolds''' (born July 9, 1929) is an American [[bluegrass music]]ian. He is best known for his innovative [[crosspicking]] and split-string styles of [[mandolin]] playing.\n\n==Biography==\nMcReynolds was born in [[Coeburn, Virginia]]. He and his brother Jim begin performing together<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p643/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Jim & Jesse|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|author2=Vinopal, David |publisher=[[All Media Guide|AMG]]|accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> in or around 1947. They originally performed under the name, \"The McReynolds Brothers.\"<ref name=\"Statman\">{{cite book | title=Bluegrass Masters: Jesse McReynolds | last=Statman|first=Andy|publisher=Oak}}</ref> In 1951, Jesse and Jim, joined by Larry Roll on guitar, made their first recording, ten gospel songs for Kentucky Records under the name \"The Virginia Trio\".<ref name=\"Statman\" /> In 1952, Jim and Jesse signed with Capitol Records, who asked them to change their name from the \"McReynolds Brothers,\" so they started recording under the name \"[[Jim and Jesse]] and the Virginia Boys.\".<ref name=\"Statman\" /> They recorded 20 songs for Capitol over three sessions in 1952, 1953, and 1955.<ref name=\"Statman\" /> During this time (1952-1954), Jesse also served in the US Army in Korea (they recorded sessions in 1953 while he was on leave).<ref name=\"Statman\" /> While serving in Korea, he and [[Charlie Louvin]] of the [[Louvin Brothers]] (who was also serving in Korea) formed a band called the \"Dusty Roads Boys\" and played regular concerts for other troops.<ref>{{cite book | title=Satan is Real: The Ballad of the Louvin Brothers | last=Louvin |first = Charlie |author2=Whitmer, Benjamin  |publisher=Igniter}}</ref> After Jesse's return from Korea, [[Jim and Jesse]] continued to perform and release albums until Jim's death from cancer in 2002. McReynolds is married to his wife, Joy.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ellen|last=Harvey|title=Owners Hope to Sing Praises of Their 2YO|date=July 19, 2010|url =http://harnesslink.com/News/Owners-hope-to-sing-praises-of-their-2yo-82207|work = Harness Racing Communications|accessdate =March 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nSince 2002, Jesse has continued to perform and record as a solo artist. McReynolds plays between 60 and 70 shows each year. Jim and Jesse became [[List of Grand Ole Opry Members|members of the Grand Ole Opry]] in 1964; Jesse continues to maintain the duo's [[Grand Ole Opry|Opry]] membership since Jim's death in 2001. He beacame the oldest standing Opry member in March of 2020, following the death of fellow Opry member [[Jan Howard]]. In 2019, he celebrated his 55th anniversary as a member of the Opry. In January 2017 he appeared on the CMT network show Nashville as a blind singer who inspires the character [[Rayna Jaymes]] (played by [[Connie Britton]]).\n\n==Honors==\n* Member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] since 1964 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opry.com/artist/jesse-mcreynolds|accessdate=July 25, 2015|title=Jesse McReynolds|date=2013-12-06}}</ref>\n* Inducted into [[International Bluegrass Music Hall of Honor]] in 1993\n* Awarded [[National Heritage Fellowship Award]] in 1997\n* ''Bending the Rules'' nominated for \"Best Instrumental Recording of the Year\" from the [[International Bluegrass Music Association]] in 2005.\n\n==Recordings<ref name=\"Statman\"/><ref>Recordings after 1979 from Old Dominion Masters liner notes</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Album(s) !! Group !! Notes\n|-\n| 1951 || The Virginia Trio 1951: Their Early Gospel Recordings (Old Dominion, 2000); ''Sacred Songs of The Virginia Trio'' (Ultrasonic) || ''The Virginia Trio'' or ''James and Jesse McReynolds with Larry Roll'' || Ten songs originally recorded as singles for the Kentucky label, later released as a single album by Ultrasonic and Old Dominion.\n|-\n| 1952,1954,1955 || ''20 Great Songs by Jim and Jesse'' (Capitol, 1968); ''First Sounds: The Capitol Years'' (2002);<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/First-Sounds-Capitol-Jim-Jesse/dp/B00006LI54/ref=sr_1_9?ie=UTF8&qid=1437856258&sr=8-9&keywords=jim+and+jesse|accessdate= July 25, 2015}}</ref> ''Jim and Jesse: 1952-1955'' (Bear Family, 1992); ''Jim and Jesse: Best of the Early Years'' (Cleopatra, 2009) || [[Jim and Jesse]] || The duo recorded 20 songs for Capitol in three sessions. These songs 