013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/golden-globe-nominations-2018-full-list-nominees-1063937/item/best-performance-by-an-actor-a-television-series-drama-1064248 |title=Golden Globes: 'Shape of Water,' 'Big Little Lies' Top Nominations |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 11, 2017 |access-date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[70th Primetime Emmy Awards|2018]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eonline.com/news/951560/in-honor-of-david-harbour-s-emmy-nom-here-is-the-stranger-things-season-3-scoop-you-need |title=David Harbour's Puppy Pooped In Celebration of His Emmy Nom|last=Piester |first=Lauren |date=July 12, 2018 |work=[[E! Online]] |access-date=July 13, 2018 |publisher=[[E! News]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[40th Golden Raspberry Awards|2020]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]]\n| ''[[Hellboy (2019 film)|Hellboy]]''\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.razzies.com/razz-newz.html|title=RAZZ NEWZ - The Razzies!|website=razzies.com}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q391359|c=Category:David Harbour|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|1092086}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|1991}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/person/29320/summary.html David Harbour] at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards for David Harbour\n|list=\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actor}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harbour, David}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from White Plains, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}} \n{{Infobox person\n| name               = David Harbour\n| image              = David Harbour by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Harbour at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = David Kenneth Harbour<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nsEO8LALcyo|title=Stranger Things' Winona Ryder & David Harbour Answer the Web's Most Searched Questions|publisher=YouTube|work=WIRED|date=July 8, 2019|accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1975|4|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[White Plains, New York]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Dartmouth College]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1999\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''David Kenneth Harbour''' (born April 10, 1975) is an American actor. He plays [[Jim Hopper (Stranger Things)|Jim Hopper]] in ''[[Stranger Things]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-01-01/david-harbour-loves-hopper-of-stranger-things-so-why-does-he-want-him-dead|title=David Harbour loves Hopper on 'Stranger Things.' So why does he want him dead?|date=January 1, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> which earned him a [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Critics' Choice Television Award]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2018/01/12/stranger-things-david-harbour-wins-critics-choice-award/|title='Stranger Things' David Harbour Wins Critics' Choice Award|website=TV Shows|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> He has also received [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Golden Globe Award]] nominations for the role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/david-harbour|title=David Harbour|website=Television Academy|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/david-harbour|title=David Harbour|website=www.goldenglobes.com|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHarbour was born on April 10, 1975 in [[White Plains, New York]], to parents Kenneth and Nancy (n\u00e9e Riley) Harbour. Both of his parents work in real estate, his mother in residential and his father in commercial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/article/playbillcoms-cue-a-merchant-of-venices-david-harbour-com-174413 |title= PLAYBILL.COM'S CUE & A: Merchant of Venice's David Harbour |work=[[Playbill]] |access-date=July 27, 2018 |last=Blank |first=Matthew |date=December 14, 2010 |publisher=Brightspot}}</ref> He attended [[Byram Hills High School]] in [[Armonk, New York]], along with actors [[Sean Maher]] and [[Eyal Podell]]. Harbour graduated from [[Dartmouth College]] in [[Hanover, New Hampshire]], in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vnews.com/From-Hanover-to-Hellboy-in-Countless-Steps-17400998|title=Valley News - Film Notes: \u2018Stranger Things\u2019 Actor David Harbour Returns to Dartmouth|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince January 19th 2020, Harbour has been in a relationship with singer [[Lily Allen]]. They made their red carpet debut during the 26th annual Screen Actors Guild Awards.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:David Harbour (17015322391).jpg|upright|thumb|left|Harbour at the [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n\nHarbour began acting professionally on Broadway in 1999, in the revival of ''[[The Rainmaker (play)|The Rainmaker]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/person/david-harbour-vault-0000056862|title=David Harbour|website=Playbill|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> He then made his television debut that same year in an episode of ''[[Law & Order]]'', playing a waiter. He appeared again in 2002 in an episode of ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', playing a child murderer. Harbour portrayed the recurring role of [[MI6]] Agent Roger Anderson in the [[American Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] series ''[[Pan Am (TV series)|Pan Am]]''. In 2005, he was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] for his performance in a production of ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]''.\n\nHarbour is also known for his role as CIA Agent [[List of Quantum of Solace characters#Gregg Beam|Gregg Beam]] in ''[[Quantum of Solace (film)|Quantum of Solace]]'', as Shep Campbell in ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]]'', and as [[Russell Crowe]]'s source in ''[[State of Play (2009 film)|State of Play]]''. He also received praise for his role as [[spree killer]] Paul Devildis in a 2009 episode of ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Fretts |first=Bruce |date=July 13, 2009 |title=Cheers & Jeers |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |page=8}}</ref> Harbour's other film credits include ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]'', ''[[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|The Green Hornet]]'', ''[[End of Watch]]'', and ''[[Between Us (2012 film)|Between Us]]''. In 2013, he played a small role of a head doctor in the television series ''[[Elementary (TV series)|Elementary]]''. From 2012 to 2014, he also played the recurring role of Elliot Hirsch in ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popsugar.com/node/42002280|title=The Newsroom|first=Maggie|last=Panos|date=November 2, 2017|website=POPSUGAR Entertainment|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Harbour played the recurring character of Dr. Reed Akley in the first season of the historical drama series ''[[Manhattan (TV series)|Manhattan]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc.com/the-tonight-show/guests/david-harbour/2067991dca8f8d72e9f9cbf515408223a2e5041b|title=David Harbour on The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon|website=NBC|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> In 2015, Harbour was cast as Chief [[Jim Hopper (character)|Jim Hopper]] in the [[Netflix]] science fiction horror series ''[[Stranger Things]]''. For his role in the series, Harbour has received nominations for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] (2017 and 2018) and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] (2018). Harbour has won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]] (2017) along with the rest of the cast.\n\nHarbour portrayed the [[Hellboy|title character]] in the film reboot ''[[Hellboy (2019 film)|Hellboy]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web |last=Perry |first=Spencer |url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/845915-neil-marshall-to-direct-hellboy-reboot-starring-david-harbour |title=Neil Marshall to Direct Hellboy Reboot Starring David Harbour! |website=[[Comingsoon.net]] |date=May 8, 2017 |accessdate=May 8, 2017}}</ref> He will also co-star as [[Red Guardian]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] film ''[[Black Widow (2020 film)|Black Widow]]'' (2020).<ref>{{cite web |last=Kit|first=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/david-harbour-joins-scarlett-johansson-black-widow-1198884|title='Stranger Things' Star David Harbour Joins Scarlett Johansson in Marvel's 'Black Widow'. (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 8, 2017 |accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/20/black-widow-movie-first-look-scarlett-johansson/ |title=Black Widow hits Comic-Con with first details of Scarlett Johansson film |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Devan |last=Coggan |date=July 20, 2019 |access-date=July 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\"|Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Kinsey (film)|Kinsey]]''\n| Robert Kinsey\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2005\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Confess (film)|Confess]]''\n| FBI Agent McAllister\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Brokeback Mountain]]''\n| Randall Malone\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[War of the Worlds (2005 film)|War of the Worlds]]''\n| Dock Worker\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Wedding Weekend''\n| David\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Revolutionary Road (film)|Revolutionary Road]]''\n| Shep Campbell\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Quantum of Solace]]''\n| Gregg Beam\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[State of Play (film)|State of Play]]''\n| PointCorp Insider\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]''\n| Brian\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|The Green Hornet]]''\n| D.A. Frank Scanlon\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[W.E.]]''\n| [[Ernest Aldrich Simpson]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2012\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[End of Watch]]''\n| Van Hauser\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Between Us (2012 film)|Between Us]]''\n| Joel\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Knife Fight (film)|Knife Fight]]''\n| Stephen Green\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Snitch (film)|Snitch]]''\n| Jay Price\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Parkland (film)|Parkland]]''\n| James Gordon Shanklin\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[X/Y]]''\n| Todd\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[A Walk Among the Tombstones (film)|A Walk Among the Tombstones]]''\n| Ray\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[The Equalizer (film)|The Equalizer]]''\n| Frank Masters\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Black Mass (film)|Black Mass]]''\n