             = \n| area_urban_km2                  = \n| area_metro_km2                  = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_footnotes            = {{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n| population_total                = 239700\n| population_as_of                = 2016\n| population_density_km2          = 2002.0\n| population_urban                = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_density_metro_km2    = \n| population_blank1_title         = Pop&nbsp;<small>2006-2011</small>\n| population_blank1               = {{increase}} 0.9%\n| population_blank2_title         = Dwellings\n| population_blank2               = 106499\n| population_note                 = \n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22125\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22124\n| postal_code_type                = [[Canadian postal code|Postal code(s)]]\n| postal_code                     = [[List of J postal codes of Canada|J3Y, J3Z, J4G to J4N, J4T, J4V]]\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 450 and 579|450 and 579]]\n| blank1_name                     = Highways <br/> {{jct|state=QC|TCH|20}} <br/> {{jct|state=QC|TCH|25}} <br/> {{jct|state=QC|A|30}}\n| blank1_info                     = <br/> {{jct|state=QC|QC|112}} <br/> {{jct|state=QC|QC|116}} <br/> {{jct|state=QC|QC|132}} <br/> {{jct|state=QC|QC|134}}\n| blank2_name                     = [[Demonym]]\n| blank2_info                     = ''Longueuillois(e)''\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.longueuil.quebec/en}}\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''Longueuil''' ({{IPAc-en|l|\u0252|\u014b|\u02c8|\u0261|e\u026a|l}}; {{IPA-fr|l\u0254\u0303\u0261\u0153j|lang}}) is a city in the province of [[Quebec]], Canada. It is the seat of the [[Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie|Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie administrative region]] and the central city of the [[urban agglomeration of Longueuil]]. It sits on the [[South Shore (Montreal)|south shore]] of the [[Saint Lawrence River]] directly across from [[Montreal]]. The population as of the [[Canada 2016 Census]] totalled 239,700, making it Montreal's second largest suburb, the fifth most populous city in Quebec and [[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|twentieth]] largest in Canada.\n\n[[Charles le Moyne de Longueuil et de Ch\u00e2teauguay|Charles Le Moyne]] founded Longueuil  as a ''[[Seigneurial system of New France|seigneurie]]'' in 1657. It would become a parish in 1845, a village in 1848, a town in 1874 and a city in 1920. Between 1961 and 2002, Longueuil's borders grew three times, as it was amalgamated with surrounding municipalities; there was a strong de-amalgamation in 2006 (see [[2000\u20132006 municipal reorganization in Quebec]]).\n\nLongueuil is a residential, commercial and industrial city. It incorporates some [[urban area|urban]] features, but is essentially a [[suburb]]. Longueuil can be classified as a [[commuter town]] as a large portion of its residents commute to work in Montreal. Most buildings are single-family homes constructed in the post-war period. The city consists of three boroughs: [[Le Vieux-Longueuil]], [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]] and [[Greenfield Park, Quebec|Greenfield Park]].\n\nLongueuil is the seat of the [[Judicial districts of Quebec|judicial district]] of Longueuil.<ref>[http://www2.publicationsduquebec.gouv.qc.ca/dynamicSearch/telecharge.php?type=2&file=/D_11/D11_A.HTM ''Territorial Division Act'']. ''Revised Statutes of Quebec'' D-11.</ref> Residents of the city are called ''Longueuillois''.\n\n==History==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2009}}\n[[File:Fort Longueuil 1825.jpg|thumb|left|Ruins of [[Fort Longueuil]] in 1825.]]\nThe territory of [[New France]] was divided into [[Seigneurial system of New France|seigneuries]] in order to ensure the colony's defence. Longueuil was founded in 1657 by [[Charles le Moyne de Longueuil et de Ch\u00e2teauguay|Charles Le Moyne]], a merchant from [[Fort Ville-Marie|Ville-Marie]] (present day Montreal), as a [[Seigneurial system of New France|seigneurie]].<ref name=\"CanadianEncyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/longueuil|title=Longueuil|last=LINTEAU|first=PAUL-ANDR\u00c9|author2=CLAIRE POITRAS |work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica-Dominion Institute]]|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref> According to Abb\u00e9 Faillon, Charles Le Moyne, lord of the area starting in 1657, named Longueuil after a village which is today the seat of a canton in the district of [[Dieppe, France|Dieppe]] in his homeland of [[Normandy]].\n\nHis son, [[Charles le Moyne de Longueuil, Baron de Longueuil|Charles Le Moyne de Longueuil]], built [[Fort Longueuil]] as his fortified residence. It was constructed of stone between 1685 and 1690 and had four towers.<ref name=\"CRHP\">{{CRHP|14401|Fort Longueuil|7 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nFort Longueuil was believed to be occupied by [[United States|American]] troops during the [[American Revolutionary War]]. It was subsequently occupied by the [[United Kingdom|British]]. It was demolished in 1810 due to its poor condition.<ref name=\"CRHP\" /> The [[Archaeology|archaeological remains]] of Fort Longueuil were recognized as a [[National Historic Site of Canada]] on May 25, 1923.  The site extends beneath the present-day [[Co-Cathedral of Saint-Antoine-de-Padoue|Saint-Antoine-de-Padoue Cathedral]].<ref name=\"CRHP\" />\n[[File:The church and Rue St. Charles, Longueuil, QC, about 1910.jpg|thumbnail|left|The [[Co-Cathedral of Saint-Antoine-de-Padoue]] and Rue St. Charles, Longueuil, QC, about 1910]]\nThe seigneurial system ended in 1845 and Longueuil was turned into a [[parish municipality (Quebec)|parish municipality]] named Saint-Antoine-de-Longueuil.<ref name=\"CanadianEncyclopedia\"/> In 1848, a portion detached from the parish and officially established as the [[Old Longueuil|village of Longueuil]]. This same village became a town in 1874, and then a city in 1920.<ref name=\"CanadianEncyclopedia\"/> Musician [[Paul Pratt]] notably served as the city's mayor from 1935-1966.\n\nLongueuil's city limits expanded for the first time in 1961 when it merged with [[Montr\u00e9al-Sud]], and again in 1969 when it merged with [[Ville Jacques-Cartier]].<ref name=\"CanadianEncyclopedia\"/> In both cases, Longueuil was chosen as the name of the new city.\n\nOn January 1, 2002, as part of the [[2000\u20132006 municipal reorganization in Quebec]], the provincial government amalgamated [[Le Vieux-Longueuil|the former Longueuil]] with [[Boucherville]], [[Brossard]], [[Greenfield Park, Quebec|Greenfield Park]], [[LeMoyne, Quebec|LeMoyne]], [[Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville]], [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]] and [[Saint-Lambert, Quebec|Saint-Lambert]]. As with the 1960s, the name Longueuil was chosen for the new city.  However, after a [[2003 Quebec general election|change of government]] and a [[2004 Quebec municipal referendums|2004 referendum]], Boucherville, Brossard, Saint-Lambert and Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville were re-constituted as independent cities on January 1, 2006.  As such, the current city of Longueuil now includes only the former cities of Longueuil (1969-2002), Saint-Hubert, Greenfield Park and LeMoyne.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Longueuil Quebec location diagram.PNG|thumb|left|Location of the city of Longueuil within the [[Urban Agglomeration of Longueuil]].]]\nLongueuil occupies 115.59&nbsp;square kilometres (44.6&nbsp;sq mi) of land. The city is bordered by the cities of [[Saint-Lambert, Quebec|Saint-Lambert]] and [[Brossard]] to the west, [[Boucherville]] and [[Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville]] to the east, and the [[Saint Lawrence River]] and Montreal to the north. The city of Longueuil is located approximately 7&nbsp;kilometres (5&nbsp;mi) south of [[Montreal]] on the [[South Shore (Montreal)|south shore]] of the [[Saint Lawrence River]].\n\nLongueuil is located in the Saint Lawrence River [[valley]], and is a vast [[plain]]. Areas near the river were originally [[swamp]] land with [[mixed forest]], and later prime agricultural land. Agricultural land still exists in the portions of the city furthest from the river.\n\nThe city of Longueuil also includes [[\u00cele Charron]], a small [[island]] in the Saint Lawrence River, and part of the [[Boucherville Islands]].\n\nLike Montreal, Longueuil is classified as [[Humid continental climate|humid continental]] or [[hemiboreal]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfb''). Longueuil has long winters, lasting from November to March, short springs during April and May, average summers, lasting from June to August, and short autumns during September and October.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport (1981-2010)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n\n|Jan maximum humidex = 15.4\n|Feb maximum humidex = 15.5\n|Mar maximum humidex = 23.4\n|Apr maximum humidex = 34.7\n|May maximum humidex = 38.7\n|Jun maximum humidex = 47.2\n|Jul maximum humidex = 46.2\n|Aug maximum humidex = 46.9\n|Sep maximum humidex = 41.8\n|Oct maximum humidex = 34.5\n|Nov maximum humidex = 24.9\n|Dec maximum humidex = 18.0\n\n|Jan record high C = 13.9\n|Feb record high C = 15.3\n|Mar record high C = 23.7\n|Apr record high C = 30.6\n|May record high C = 33.3\n|Jun record high C = 35.0\n|Jul record high C = 35.6\n|Aug record high C = 35.6\n|Sep record high C = 33.8\n|Oct record high C = 28.9\n|Nov record high C = 22.8\n|Dec record high C = 17.1\n\n|Jan high C = -5.6\n|Feb high C = -3.2\n|Mar high C = 2.3\n|Apr high C = 11.3\n|May high C = 19.1\n|Jun high C = 23.8\n|Jul high C = 26.3\n|Aug high C = 25.4\n|Sep high C = 20.5\n|Oct high C = 13.0\n|Nov high C = 5.6\n|Dec high C = -1.5\n\n|Jan mean C = -10.4\n|Feb mean C = -8.2\n|Mar mean C = -2.5\n|Apr mean C = 5.7\n|May mean C = 12.9\n|Jun mean C = 17.9\n|Jul mean C = 20.6\n|Aug mean C = 19.5\n|Sep mea