dian|White]] || 193,360 || 84.8\n|-\n| [[Black Canadians|Black]] || 10,500 || 4.6\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] || 5,810 || 2.5\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadians|Arab]] || 5,290|| 2.3\n|-\n| [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] || 2,870 || 1.3\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asia]]n || 2,605 || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Berbers|Berber]] ||2,085 || 0.9\n|-\n| [[First Nations]] || 1,330 || 0.6\n|-\n| [[Western Asia|West Asian]] || 1,275 || 0.6\n|-\n| [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]] || 645 || 0.3\n|-\n| Multiple visible minority || 560 || 0.2\n|-\n| Other visible minority || 545 || 0.2\n|-\n| [[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]] || 480 || 0.2\n|-\n| [[Korean Canadian|Korean]] || 195 || 0\n|-\n| Other aboriginal identities || 180 || 0\n|-\n| [[Japanese Canadians|Japanese]] || 170 || 0\n|-\n| [[Inuit]] || 50 || 0\n|-\n| Multiple aboriginal identities || 25 || 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''''Total population''''' || '''''227,970''''' || '''''100'''''\n|}\nAccording to the [[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Canadian Census]], the city of Longueuil had 231,409 people, an increase of 0.9% over 2006's figure of 229,330. Longueuil occupies 115.59 square kilometres of space, giving the city a population density of 2,002 persons per kilometre squared. There were 106,499 private dwellings, 102,067 of which were occupied by usual residents.\n\nOf the 132,570 workers in Longueuil, the median income was $26,537, which is above Quebec's provincial average of $25,464. Among the 69,990 full-time workers, the median income was $37,521 or slightly below the provincial average.<ref name=\"income\">{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=2458227&Geo2=PR&Code2=24&Data=Count&SearchText=Longueuil&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Income%20and%20earnings&Custom=|title=Income and earnings for Longueuil|date=April 30, 2008|work=[[Canada 2006 Census]]|publisher=Statistics Canada|accessdate=2008-05-17}}</ref> Several of Montreal's most impoverished neighborhoods are located in Longueuil.<ref name=\"Radio-Canada\">{{cite web | title = Des familles montr\u00e9alaises aux revenus modestes optent pour la Rive-Sud | url = http://blogues.radio-canada.ca/rive-sud/2012/06/04/logements-longueuil/ | date = 2012-06-04 | accessdate = 2013-06-14 | language = French | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130615114637/http://blogues.radio-canada.ca/rive-sud/2012/06/04/logements-longueuil/ | archive-date = 2013-06-15 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nAs of the [[Canada 2011 Census|2011 Canadian Census]], [[French language|French]] was the [[First language|mother tongue]] language of 81.4% of Longueuil's residents while [[English language|English]] was the first language of 7.5%. Other languages were spoken by 13.6% of the population, with the most spoken being [[Spanish language|Spanish]] (3.0%), [[Arabic]] (2.1%), [[Haitian Creole language|Haitian Creole]] (1.2%), [[Romanian language|Romanian]] (0.7%), [[Persian language|Persian]] (0.7%), [[Chinese language|Chinese]] (0.6%), [[Italian language|Italian]] (0.6%) and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] (0.6%).<ref name=\"language2006\">{{cite web | title = Longueuil, V. | work =  Detailed Mother Tongue (192), Single and Multiple Language Responses (3), Age Groups (7) and Sex (3) for the Population Excluding Institutional Residents of Canada, Provinces, Territories, Census Divisions and Census Subdivisions, 2011 Census | publisher = Statistics Canada | date = 2012-10-24 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/tbt-tt/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=1&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=103251&PRID=0&PTYPE=101955&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2011&THEME=90&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF= | accessdate = 2012-10-24}}</ref> These figures include multiple responses.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=\"19\"|Canada Census Mother Tongue - Longueuil, Quebec\n|-\n|+Mother tongue language\n! Census\n|\n! Total\n|colspan=\"1\"| \n!colspan=\"3\"|{{center|French}}\n|colspan=\"1\"|\n!colspan=\"3\"|{{center|English}}\n|colspan=\"1\"|\n!colspan=\"3\"|{{center|French & English}}\n|colspan=\"1\"|\n!colspan=\"3\"|{{center|Other}}\n|-\n! Year\n|\n! Responses\n| \n! Count\n! Trend\n! Pop %\n|\n! Count\n! Trend\n! Pop %\n|\n! Count\n! Trend\n! Pop %\n|\n! Count\n! Trend\n! Pop %\n|-\n| {{center|2016}}\n|\n| {{center|237,665}}\n|\n| 182,705\n| {{increase}} 0.49%\n| 76.87%\n|\n| 13,900\n| {{decrease}} 1.8%\n| 5.84%\n|\n| 2,485\n| {{increase}} 0.1%\n| 1.04%\n|\n| 34,310\t\n| {{increase}} 22.1%\n| 14.44%\n|-\n| {{center|2011}}\n|\n| {{center|229,550}}\n|\n| 181,800\n| {{increase}} 0.0005%\n| 79.21%\n|\n| 14,155\n| {{decrease}} 8.05%\n| 6.17%\n|\n| 2,460\n| {{increase}} 37.05%\n| 1.07%\n|\n| 28,115\n| {{increase}} 0.97%\n| 12.25%\n|-\n| {{center|2006}}\n|\n| {{center|226,820}}\n|\n| 181,790\t\n| {{decrease}} 1.40%\n| 80.15%\n|\n| 15,395\t\n| {{increase}} 10.87%\n| 6.79%\n|\n| 1,795\t\n| {{decrease}} 4.5%\n| 0.81%\n|\n| 27,845\n| {{increase}} 56.86%\n| 12.28%\n|-\n| {{center|2001}}\n|\n| {{center|218,810}}\n|\n| 184,380\t\n| {{increase}} 0.39%\n| 84.26%\n|\n| 13,885\n| {{decrease}} 17.22%\n| 6.35%\n|\n| 1,880\n| {{decrease}} 17.74%\n| 0.86%\n|\n| 17,795\n| {{increase}} 5.95%\n| 8.13%\n|-\n| {{center|1996}}\n|\n| {{center|220600}}\n|\n| 183,065\t\n| n/a\n| 82.99%\n|\n| 16,775\n| n/a\n| 7.60%\n|\n| 2,285\n| n/a\n| 1.04%\n|\n| 16,795\n| n/a\n| 7.61%\n|}\n\nPeople of [[Ethnic groups in Europe|European origins]] made up 87.6% of the population in 2006. The largest visible minority groups are [[Black Canadian|Black]] (4.1%), [[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]] (2%), [[Arab Canadian|Arab]] (1.6%), [[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]] (1.2%), Southeast Asian (1%), and South Asian (0.7%).<ref name=\"SC2006\">[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/profiles/community/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=2458227&Geo2=PR&Code2=24&Data=Count&SearchText=Longueuil&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&Custom= 2006 Community Profiles - Longueuil]</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===2016 population by mother tongue===\n====Ville de Longueuil====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Top 20 languages Longueuil, 2016<ref>[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=2466023&Geo2=CD&Code2=2466&Data=Count&SearchText=montreal&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 Longueuil Profile], Longueuil 2016</ref> !! Population !! %\n|-\n|[[French language|French]]|| 182,705 || 79.1\n|-\n|[[English language|English]] || 13,900 || 6.0\n|-\n|[[Spanish language|Spanish]]|| 7,830 || 3.4\n|-\n|[[Arabic]]|| 5,235 || 2.3\n|-\n|[[French-based creole languages|Creole]]|| 2,805 || 1.2\n|-\n|[[Romanian language|Romanian]]|| 1,985 || 1.0\n|-\n|[[Persian language|Farsi]]|| 1,885 || 0.8\n|-\n|[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]|| 1,475 || 0.6\n|-\n|[[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]|| 1,390 || 0.6\n|-\n|[[Russian language|Russian]]|| 1,180 || 0.5\n|-\n|[[Italian language|Italian]]|| 1,160 || 0.5\n|-\n|[[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]|| 970 || 0.4\n|-\n|[[Cantonese]]|| 845 || 0.4\n|-\n|[[Kabyle language|Kabyle]]|| 575 || 0.2\n|-\n|[[Greek language|Greek]]|| 565 || 0.2\n|-\n|[[Polish language|Polish]]|| 345 || 0.1\n|-\n|[[Lao language|Lao]]|| 340 || 0.1\n|-\n|[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]|| 330 || 0.1\n|-\n|[[Wolof language|Wolof]]|| 305 || 0.1\n|-\n|[[German language|German]]|| 280 || 0.1\n|}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:145, rue Saint-Charles Ouest, Longueuil.jpg|alt=|thumb|[[Old Longueuil]]]]\nAlthough a large chunk of Longueuil's work force commute to Montreal, the city nevertheless offers many jobs in a diverse range of industries. Above all, Longueuil benefits from having very low [[property value]] despite its close proximity to Montreal.\n\nLongueuil is particularly strong in the [[aerospace]] industry. It is home to the headquarters of both [[Pratt & Whitney Canada]] and [[H\u00e9roux-Devtek]]. Pratt & Whitney Canada is Longueuil's top employer with 5,000 employees, while H\u00e9roux-Devtek has 550 employees.<ref name=InfoAffaires>{{cite web|title=Les 200 plus grandes entreprises|url=http://virtuel.informationaffaires.ca/doc/hebdo_l-informations-d-affaires-rive-sud/iar2013-01-14/2013011101/#20|publisher=L' Information d'Affaires Rive-Sud|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref>  Also located in Longueuil is the headquarters of the [[Canadian Space Agency]] ([[John H. Chapman Space Center]]), adjacent to [[Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport]].<ref>\"[http://www.asc-csa.gc.ca/eng/contact.asp Contact us].\" [[Canadian Space Agency]]. Retrieved on January 8, 2012.</ref> [[Pascan Aviation]] has its headquarters in [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]], Longueuil.<ref>\"[http://www.pascan.com/en/contact/ Contact us].\" [[Pascan Aviation]]. Retrieved on December 4, 2010.</ref> Other companies based in Longueuil include [[Agropur]], [[Innergex Renewable Energy]], and the Canadian subsidiary of [[Hasbro]].<ref>https://www.tvanouvelles.ca/2016/06/21/agropur-inaugure-son-nouveau-siege-social</ref><ref>https://www.hasbro.com/en-ca/customer-service</ref>\n\nIn 2008, [[Canadian Business]] ranked Longueuil as the 30th best place to do business in Canada.<ref name=\"CdnBsn\">{{cite web|url=http://list.canadianbusiness.com/rankings/best-places-to-do-business/2008/Default.aspx?sp2=1&d1=a&sc1=7|title=The Best Places to do Business in Canada|year=2008|publisher=[[Canadian Business]]|accessdate=2008-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081106051524/http://list.canadianbusiness.com/rankings/best-places-to-do-business/2008/Default.aspx?sp2=1&d1=a&sc1=7|archive-date=2008-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and culture==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2013}}\nThe [[Longueuil International Percussion Festival]], which features 500 musicians, takes place over six days in July in the neighbourhood of [[Old Longueuil]], and draws 200,000 visitors per year.<ref name=\"loto\">{{cite web|url=http://lotoquebec.com/rendezvous/nav/en/festivals-events/international-percussion-festival-of-longueuil|title=International Percussion Festival of Longueuil PrintPrint|year=2012|work=Les Rendez-Vous Loto-Qu\u00e9bec|publisher=[[Loto-Qu\u00e9bec]]|accessdate=28 June 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508174457/http://lotoquebec.com/rendezvous/nav/en/festivals-events/international-percussion-festival-of-longueuil|archivedate=8 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Parc Marie-Victorin, Longueuil 001.jpg|alt=|thumb|Marie-Victorin Park, Longueuil. The Montreal Olympic stadium can be seen in the distance]]\n{{Expand section|date=March 2013}}\nThere are three [[nature parks]] in Longueuil, [[Parc Marie-Victorin]] and [[Parc Michel-Chartrand]] in Le Vieux-Longueuil and [[Parc de la Cit\u00e9]] in Saint-Hubert. It is also home to a [[Wildlife sanctuary|wildlife reserve]], the [[Bois\u00e9 du Tremblay]], which is partially in Le Vieux-Longueuil and partially in [[Boucherville]].\n\nThere are seven arenas: Cynthia Coull Arena in Greenfield Park; Ar\u00e9na \u00c9mile-Butch-Bouchard, Ar\u00e9na Jacques-Cartier, Ar\u00e9na Olympia and [[Colis\u00e9e Jean B\u00e9liveau]] in Le Vieux-Longueuil; and Centre sportif Ga\u00e9tan-Boucher and Centre sportif Rosanne-Laflamme in Saint-Hubert.\n\nNotable places of worship include the [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] [[Co-Cathedral of Saint-Antoine-de-Padoue]], the [[\u00c9glise Nouvelle vie]] evangelical church, {{Interlanguage link multi|Saint-Hubert Church|fr|3=\u00c9glise de Saint-Hubert (Longueuil)|vertical-align=sup}}, and the [[Montr\u00e9al Qu\u00e9bec Temple]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].\n\n==Sport==\n{{Prose|section|date=March 2013}}\n{{Expand section|date=March 2013}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+Sports teams based in Longueuil\n|-\n! Team\n! Sport\n! League\n! Venue\n|-\n| [[Lynx du Coll\u00e8ge \u00c9douard-Montpetit women's ice hockey|Coll\u00e8ge \u00c9douard-Montpetit Lynx]]\n| [[Women's ice hockey]]\n| [[Hockey coll\u00e9gial f\u00e9minin RSEQ]]\n| [[Ar\u00e9na \u00c9mile Butch Bouchard]]\n|-\n| [[CS Longueuil]]\n| [[Association football|Soccer]]\n| [[Premi\u00e8re Ligue de soccer du Qu\u00e9bec]]\n| Centre Multi-Sport\n|-\n| [[Le Coll\u00e8ge Fran\u00e7ais de Longueuil]]\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| [[Quebec Junior AAA Hockey League]]\n| [[Colis\u00e9e Jean B\u00e9liveau]]\n|-\n| [[Longueuil Ducs]]\n| [[Baseball]]\n| [[Ligue de Baseball \u00c9lite du Qu\u00e9bec]]\n| [[Parc Paul-Pratt]]\n|-\n| [[South Shore JR Bruizers]]\n| [[Canadian football]]\n| [[Quebec Junior Football League]]\n| Parc Rosanne Laflamme\n|}\n\n==Government==\n\n===Municipal===\n{{Main|Longueuil City Council}}\n[[File:Longueuil City Hall 2011.jpg|thumb|Longueuil City Hall is located in the borough of [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]].]]\nThe mayor is Sylvie Parent, who was elected on Nov. 5, 2017.<ref>https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/recount-confirms-sylvie-parent-as-longueuil-mayor</ref> She is the fourth mayor of Longueuil since the 2002 [[Municipal reorganization in Quebec|merger]]. Businessman [[Jacques Olivier]] who once served as [[Minister of Labour (Canada)|Minister of Labour]] served as mayor from 2002 until 2005. The second mayor of Longueuil was [[Claude Gladu]], serving from 2006 to 2009. He also happened to be mayor of the former city of Longueuil from 1994 to 2002. Former member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]], [[Caroline St-Hilaire]] was the third mayor from 2009-2017.\n\nThe city's three boroughs are [[Le Vieux-Longueuil]], [[Greenfield Park, Quebec|Greenfield Park]] and [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]]. In total there are 26 [[Longueuil City Council|city councillors]], including one borough president each. Greenfield Park has three councillors and its borough president is Mireille Carri\u00e8re of Action Longueuil. Saint-Hubert has eight councillors and its borough president is Lorraine Guay-Boivin of Action Longueuil. Le Vieux-Longueuil has fifteen councillors and its borough president is Michel Desjardins of the Parti municipal de Longueuil.\n\nLongueuil's city hall is located in the borough of Saint-Hubert, on the edge of the city.\n\n===Federal and provincial===\nFederally, Longueuil is part of three electoral districts. The riding of [[Longueuil\u2014Charles-LeMoyne]], is represented by [[Sherry Romanado]].<ref>http://www.ourcommons.ca/Parliamentarians/en/constituencies/Longueuil-Charles-LeMoyne</ref> The riding of [[Longueuil-Saint-Hubert]] is represented by [[Pierre Nantel]].  The riding of [[Montarville]], is represented by [[Michel Picard (politician)]].<ref>http://www.ourcommons.ca/Parliamentarians/en/constituencies/Montarville(685).</ref><ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=res&dir=cir/list&document=index338&lang=e#change</ref>\n\nProvincially, Longueuil is represented in four electoral districts. The electoral district of [[Laporte (electoral district)|Laporte]] includes the boroughs of Greenfield Park and Saint-Hubert, and is represented by [[Nicole M\u00e9nard]] of the [[Quebec Liberal Party]]. The electoral district of [[Marie-Victorin (electoral district)|Marie-Victorin]], which includes the western portion of Le Vieux-Longueuil, is represented by [[Catherine Fournier]] of the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] (PQ). The electoral district of [[Taillon]], which covers the eastern portion of Le Vieux-Longueuil is represented by [[Marie Malavoy]] of the PQ. The electoral district of [[Vachon (electoral district)|Vachon]], which covers the borough of [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]], is represented by [[Martine Ouellet]] of the PQ.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Commuting patterns===\n[[File:LongueuilMetro.jpg|thumb|right|The exterior of the [[Longueuil\u2013Universit\u00e9-de-Sherbrooke (Montreal Metro)|Longueuil\u2013Universit\u00e9-de-Sherbrooke]] station.]]\nAccording to the 2006 Census, about 39,485 city residents (17.2% of the total population) commute to work in Montreal on a daily basis, while only 38,090 residents (16.6%) work in the city itself. A further 6,915 residents (3.0%) work in Boucherville every day, 4,775 (2.1%) work in Brossard, 2,795 (1.2%) in Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville, and 1,815 (0.8%) work in Saint-Lambert, the four other constituent cities of the Longueuil agglomeration.\n\nBy contrast only 8,845 people commute from Montreal to work in Longueuil every day, while 4,080 people commute from Brossard to work in Longueuil, 2,940 people commute from Boucherville, 2,090 from Sainte-Julie, 1,825 from Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville, 1,815 from Chambly, and 1,810 from Saint-Jean-sur-Richelieu.<ref>{{cite web | title = Longueuil, V (Que.) | work =  Commuting Flow Census Subdivisions: Sex (3) for the Employed Labour Force 15 Years and Over Having a Usual Place of Work of Census Subdivisions, Flows Greater than or Equal to 20, 2006 Census - 20% Sample Data | publisher = Statistics Canada | date = 2008-04-02 | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/topics/RetrieveProductTable.cfm?ALEVEL=3&APATH=3&CATNO=97-561-XCB2006011&DETAIL=0&DIM=&DS=99&FL=0&FREE=0&GAL=&GC=99&GK=NA&GRP=0&IPS=97-561-XCB2006011&METH=0&ORDER=&PID=90656&PTYPE=88971&RL=0&ShowAll=&StartRow=&SUB=&Temporal=2006&Theme=76&VID=&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&S=1&O=D&A=W&PRID=0&GID=2458227 | accessdate = 2008-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===Roads===\n[[File:Boulevard Jacques-Cartier, Longueuil 01.jpg|alt=|thumb|Boulevard Jacques-Cartier Est, at the intersection of boulevard Roland-Therrien]]\nThe [[Saint Lawrence River]] between the [[Island of Montreal]] and the south shore is traversed by only five automobile crossings. Two of these are in Longueuil, the [[Louis Hippolyte Lafontaine Tunnel]] (part of [[Quebec Autoroute 25|Autoroute 25]]) and the [[Jacques Cartier Bridge]] (part of [[Quebec Route 134|Route 134]]).\n\n[[Quebec Autoroute 20|Autoroute 20]] is an important highway in Longueuil, bordering the Saint Lawrence River in the [[Le Vieux-Longueuil]] borough, where it co-exists with Autoroute Ren\u00e9-L\u00e9vesque (Route 132), and finally heading eastward toward [[Boucherville]]. [[Quebec Autoroute 30|Autoroute 30]] crosses the [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]] borough in the southern part of the city, between the cities of [[Brossard]] and [[Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville]].\n\n[[Quebec Route 116|Route 116]] is another major highway, with its western terminus located in [[LeMoyne, Quebec|LeMoyne]], heading east through the borough of Saint-Hubert toward Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville. [[Quebec Route 112|Route 112]] co-exists with Route 116 from LeMoyne to Cousineau Boulevard in Saint-Hubert, where it heads southeast toward [[Carignan, Quebec|Carignan]]. [[Quebec Route 134|Route 134]] is a major artery, perhaps better known by its more common names: the Jacques Cartier Bridge on the portion crossing the Saint-Lawrence River, and [[Taschereau Boulevard]] which connects the bridge to all three boroughs of Longueuil, and southward toward the city of Brossard.\n\n===Public transportation===\n[[File:Longueuilbus.png|thumb|right|A [[R\u00e9seau de transport de Longueuil]] bus.]]\nThe [[R\u00e9seau de transport de Longueuil|R\u00e9seau de transport de Longueuil (RTL)]] provides [[bus service]] in Longueuil. There are 77 bus routes and 12 [[shared taxi]] routes serving 139,374 passengers per day, and 32,738,155 passengers in 2011.<ref name=\"RTL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rtl-longueuil.qc.ca/images/statistique.pdf|title=Portrait de la client\u00e8le|date=December 31, 2010|work=Statistics|publisher=R\u00e9seau de transport de Longueuil|language=French|accessdate=2011-10-02}}</ref> Almost all bus lines of the RTL terminate at the [[Terminus Longueuil|Longueuil Bus Terminus]]. Many buses terminating at the other main bus terminus, [[Terminus Brossard-Panama|Brossard-Panama]], cross the [[Champlain Bridge (Montreal)|Champlain Bridge]] to arrive at the [[Terminus Centre-Ville]] in downtown Montreal (under the [[1000 de la Gaucheti\u00e8re]] office tower, at [[Bonaventure (Montreal Metro)|Bonaventure Metro]]).\n[[File:Entrance of Longueuil Marina, Quebec, Canada - panoramio.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Entrance of Longueuil Marina, Quebec, Canada]]\nThe city is also served by the [[Longueuil\u2013Universit\u00e9-de-Sherbrooke (Montreal Metro)|Longueuil\u2013Universit\u00e9-de-Sherbrooke]] [[Montreal Metro|Metro]] station, adjacent to the Longueuil bus terminus. The station connects to downtown [[Montreal]] via the [[Yellow Line (Montreal Metro)|Yellow Line]] of the Metro. The [[R\u00e9seau de transport m\u00e9tropolitain]] (RTM) runs the [[Mont-Saint-Hilaire line|Mont-Saint-Hilaire]] [[R\u00e9seau de transport m\u00e9tropolitain#Commuter trains|commuter train]] line also serves the south shore. The only commuter train station in the city of Longueuil is [[Longueuil\u2013Saint-Hubert station]]. Until the mid-1950s, Longueuil was served by interurban streetcars operated by the [[Montreal and Southern Counties Railway]].\n\nLongueuil also has a small airport, [[Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport|Saint-Hubert Airport]]. It is one of Canada's most important [[general aviation]] airports, ranked [[List of the busiest airports in Canada|12th busiest airport]] by aircraft movements.<ref name=\"move\">[http://www.tc.gc.ca/pol/EN/Report/TP577/pdf/TP577_07.pdf - Aircraft Movement Statistics: NAV CANADA Towers and Flight Service Stations: Annual Report 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213121245/http://www.tc.gc.ca/pol/EN/Report/TP577/pdf/TP577_07.pdf |date=February 13, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nA small [[marina]], the ''[[R\u00e9al Bouvier|R\u00e9al-Bouvier]] Marina'' is located on the [[Saint Lawrence River]] in the borough of [[Le Vieux-Longueuil]]. The [[Old Port of Montreal\u2013Longueuil Ferry]] is a seasonal [[ferry]] service links the R\u00e9al-Bouvier Marina to the Jacques Cartier Pier in the [[Old Port of Montreal]].<ref name=\"ferry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.longueuil.ca/vw/asp/gabarits/Gabarit.asp?ID_MESSAGE=2140&CAT_RAC=12|title=River Ferries and Boats|date=2003\u20132012|publisher=Ville de Longueuil|accessdate=15 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Hospitals===\n{{Expand section|date=March 2009}}\nThe city is served by two hospitals. The [[Charles-LeMoyne Hospital]] is a [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]] affiliated hospital in the borough of [[Greenfield Park, Quebec|Greenfield Park]]. It is the main hospital for Longueuil, as well as the neighbouring cities of [[Saint-Lambert, Quebec|Saint-Lambert]] and [[Brossard]].<ref name=\"CharlesLeMoyne\">{{cite web|url=http://www.santemonteregie.qc.ca/hclm/apropos/hclm/territoire.en.html|title=Territoire desservi|year=2008|work=[[Charles LeMoyne Hospital]]|publisher=Sant\u00e9 Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie|language=French|accessdate=20 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702011550/http://www.santemonteregie.qc.ca/hclm/apropos/hclm/territoire.en.html|archive-date=2 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Pierre-Boucher Hospital]] is a smaller hospital in the borough of [[Le Vieux-Longueuil]] which serves Le Vieux-Longueuil, [[Boucherville]], [[Varennes, Quebec|Varennes]], [[Sainte-Julie, Quebec|Sainte-Julie]], [[Saint-Amable, Quebec|Saint-Amable]], [[Verch\u00e8res, Quebec|Verch\u00e8res]], [[Calixa-Lavall\u00e9e, Quebec|Calixa-Lavall\u00e9e]] and [[Contrec\u0153ur, Quebec|Contrec\u0153ur]].<ref name=\"PierreBoucher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.santemonteregie.qc.ca/cssspierreboucher/apropos/csss-pb/territoire.fr.html|title=Territoire desservi|year=2008|work=[[Pierre Boucher Hospital|CSSS Pierre-Boucher]]|publisher=Sant\u00e9 Mont\u00e9r\u00e9gie|language=French|accessdate=20 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914155019/http://www.santemonteregie.qc.ca/cssspierreboucher/apropos/csss-pb/territoire.fr.html|archivedate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Campus de Longueuil - Universite de Sherbrooke 01.jpg|thumbnail|The Longueuil campus of [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]]. ]]\n[[File:Cegep Edouard Monpetit.jpg|thumb|left|[[Coll\u00e8ge \u00c9douard-Montpetit]], the only French CEGEP in Longueuil]]\nThe city of Longueuil is served by several educational institutions. Both the [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]] and [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]]  maintain campuses in the [[Le Vieux-Longueuil|Borough of Le Vieux-Longueuil]].\n\nThere is one [[CEGEP]] in Longueuil, [[Coll\u00e8ge \u00c9douard-Montpetit]], located in Le Vieux-Longueuil. Coll\u00e8ge \u00c9douard-Montpetit has an aerotechnic school, [[\u00c9cole nationale d'a\u00e9rotechnique]] located at a separate campus in the borough of [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]] near [[Montr\u00e9al/Saint-Hubert Airport|Saint-Hubert Airport]].\n\nThere are two technical and professional colleges, both located in Le Vieux-Longueuil: these are the Pierre-Dupuy Professional Formation Centre and Coll\u00e8ge Info-Technique.\n\n===Primary and secondary schools===\nPublic [[English language|anglophone]] schools are operated by the [[Riverside School Board]]. There are three secondary schools in Longueuil operated by the Riverside School Board: [[Centennial Regional High School]] in [[Greenfield Park, Quebec|Greenfield Park]], [[Heritage Regional High School]] in [[Saint-Hubert, Quebec|Saint-Hubert]], and [[Saint-Lambert International High School]] in [[Saint-Lambert, Quebec|Saint-Lambert]].\n\nPublic [[French language|francophone]] schools are operated by the [[Commission scolaire Marie-Victorin]]. There are seven secondary schools in Longueuil operated by that district. [[\u00c9cole secondaire Internationale St-Edmond]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire Participative l'Agora]] are in Greenfield Park. [[\u00c9cole secondaire Andr\u00e9-Laurendeau]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire Mgr-A.M.-Parent]] are in Saint-Hubert. [[\u00c9cole secondaire G\u00e9rard-Filion]], [[\u00c9cole secondaire Jacques-Rousseau]] and [[\u00c9cole secondaire St-Jean-Baptiste]] are in Le Vieux-Longueuil.\n\nPrior to 1998 the [[South Shore Protestant Regional School Board]] served the municipality.<ref>King, M.J. (Chairperson of the board). \"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=863&dat=19651216&id=WM0tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wCoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3288,6471414 South Shore Protestant Regional School Board]\" (St. Johns, PQ). ''[[The News and Eastern Townships Advocate]]''. Volume 119, No. 5. Thursday December 16, 1965. p. 2. Retrieved from [[Google News]] on November 23, 2014.</ref>\n\nThere are also three [[Private school|private]] francophone secondary schools, all of which are in Le Vieux-Longueuil. They are [[Coll\u00e8ge Charles-Lemoyne]], [[Coll\u00e8ge Fran\u00e7ais (Longueuil)|Coll\u00e8ge Fran\u00e7ais]] and [[Coll\u00e8ge Notre-Dame-de-Lourdes]].\n\n==Media==\nLongueuil and the other cities in the agglomeration are served by two free weekly [[French language|French-language]] newspapers. [[Le Courrier du Sud]], published by [[Quebecor Media]], is the oldest, and contains inserts tailored to specific boroughs (\"Le Journal de Saint-Hubert\" for Saint-Hubert and \"Le Magazine\" for Greenfield Park, LeMoyne and the city of Saint-Lambert). [[Rive-Sud Express]] is a newer weekly, published by [[Transcontinental Media]]. Both \"Le Courrier du Sud\" and \"Rive-Sud Express\" are both home delivered as well as available in newspaper boxes. [http://www.pointsud.ca/fr/ Point Sud] is an independent monthly newspaper, also free of charge, that is carried on newspaper stands\n\nLongueuil is also served by the [[CHAA-FM|CHAA-FM 103.3]] radio station. Another radio station, [[CHMP-FM|CHMP-FM 98.5]] is officially licensed to Longueuil, despite both the studio and transmitter being located in Montreal. Residents of Longueuil and adjacent communities are also served by a local cable television station, [http://www.tvrs.ca/ T\u00e9l\u00e9 Rive-Sud (TVRS)], which is owned by Quebecor Media and is an affiliate of [[Canal Vox]]. It is available to [[Videotron]] cable subscribers only.\n\n==Partner cities==\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}}  [[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]], [[Louisiana]], [[United States]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lecentre.org/discover_lecentre_english_sister.asp |title=Lafayette's Sister Cities |publisher=City of Lafayette |accessdate=2009-10-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106010319/http://www.lecentre.org/discover_lecentre_english_sister.asp |archivedate=2010-01-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Judith Sainte-Marie]], painter<ref name=\"GOC\">{{cite web |title=Artists in Canada |url=https://app.pch.gc.ca/application/aac-aic/artiste_detailler_ind-artist_detail_ind.app?rID=14401&fID=2&lang=en&qlang=en&pID=1&anm=Sainte-Marie%2C+Judith&sort=AM_ASC&ps=50&pID1=912&ps1=50&ansf=TAM&sort1=ascending |website=Artist/Maker name \"Sainte-Marie, Judith\" |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=10 December 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Jon Lajoie]], comedian\n* [[Maxime Comtois]], prospect of the [[Anaheim Ducks]]\n* [[Anthony Mantha]], ice hockey player for the [[Detroit Red Wings]]\n* [[Zviane]], graphic novelist\n* [[Abraham Toro]], Major League Baseball infielder for the [[Houston Astros]]\n\n==See also==\n* Michel Pratt, Michel Pratt, Longueuil 1657-2007 (French)\n* Michel Pratt, ''[http://marigot.ca/DictioLongueuil/Dictionnaire.htm Dictionnaire historique de Longueuil]'', version multim\u00e9dia, \u00c9ditions histoire Qu\u00e9bec\n*[[Baron de Longueuil]]\n*[[List of cities in Quebec]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[https://www.longueuil.quebec/en/  Official website]\n*[http://marigot.ca/DictioLongueuil/Dictionnaire.htm  Michel Pratt, ''Dictionnaire historique de Longueuil'']\n*[http://marigot.ca/Longueuil1657.pdf Michel Pratt, ''Longueuil 1657-2007''] {{in lang|fr}}\n<br/>\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n| title = '''Adjacent Municipal Subdivisions'''\n| Northwest = \n| North = [[Boucherville]]\n| Northeast = \n| West = ''[[Saint Lawrence River]]''<br />[[File:F