yID%3D488\n | publisher = Canadian Communications Foundation\n | year = 2012a\n | access-date = 2013-01-10\n | location = Toronto\n | ref = harv\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161005114303/http://www.broadcasting-history.ca/index3.html?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.broadcasting-history.ca%2Flistings_and_histories%2Fradio%2Fhistories.php%3Fid%3D676%26historyID%3D488\n | archive-date = 5 October 2016\n | url-status = dead\n | df = dmy-all\n }}\n*{{cite web\n | author = Environment Canada\n | url = ftp://ftp.tor.ec.gc.ca/Pub/Normals/English/\n | title = Canadian Climate Normals 1981\u20142010: Sydney A, Nova Scotia\n | work = National Climate Data and Information Archive\n | accessdate = December 3, 2013\n | publisher = Environment Canada\n | location = Ottawa\n | year = 2013\n | ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Hourly Data: Sydney, Nova Scotia\n |url         = http://www.climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climateData/hourlydata_e.html?timeframe=1&Prov=XX&StationID=6486&Year=2012&Month=5&Day=22\n |work        = National Climate Data and Information Archive\n |publisher   = [[Queen's Printer for Canada]]\n |access-date  = 2012-05-23\n |author      = Environment Canada\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130612063050/http://www.climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climateData/hourlydata_e.html?timeframe=1&Prov=XX&StationID=6486&Year=2012&Month=5&Day=22\n |archive-date = 12 June 2013\n |location    = Ottawa\n |date        = 2012-05-10\n |year        = 2012b\n |ref         = harv\n |url-status    = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n*{{cite web\n |title       = History\n |url         = http://38.108.70.85/lang_en/index.php?page=27844&id_equipe=8&currentseason=112\n |work        = Cape Breton Screaming Eagles\n |publisher   = Quebec Major Junior Hockey League\n |archive-url  = https://www.webcitation.org/6A1RsvPzS?url=http://38.108.70.85/lang_en/index.php?page=27844&id_equipe=8&currentseason=112\n |archive-date = 19 August 2012\n |location    = Montreal\n |year        = 2012\n |ref         = {{harvid|Quebec Major Junior Hockey League|(2012)}}\n |access-date = 10 November 2018\n |url-status    = dead\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n*{{cite web\n |last        = Kernaghan\n |first       = Lois\n |title       = University College of Cape Breton\n |url         = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/university-college-of-cape-breton\n |work        = The Canadian Encyclopedia\n |publisher   = Institute Historica/Dominion Institute\n |access-date  = 2013-01-06\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130519141733/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/university-college-of-cape-breton\n |archive-date = 19 May 2013\n |url-status     = live\n |location    = Toronto\n |year        = 2012\n |ref         = harv\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |url         = http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0913&Geo2=CSD&Code2=1217030&Data=Count&SearchText=Sydney&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=12&B1=All&Custom=\n |title       = Cape Breton \u2013 Sydney, Nova Scotia (Code 0913) and Cape Breton, Nova Scotia (Code 1217030) (table). Census Profile\n |author      = Statistics Canada\n |authorlink  = Statistics Canada\n |work        = 2011 Census. Statistics Canada Catalogue no. 98-316-XWE\n |publisher   = Queen's Printer for Canada\n |location    = Ottawa\n |access-date  = 2012-05-16\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130207115404/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0913&Geo2=CSD&Code2=1217030&Data=Count&SearchText=Sydney&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=12&B1=All&Custom=\n |archive-date = 7 February 2013\n |year        = 2012a\n |ref         = harv\n |url-status    = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title       = Map: Cape Breton \u2013 Sydney (Population Centre), Nova Scotia\n |url         = http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page_Map-Carte.cfm?Lang=E&Tab=3&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0913&Geo2=CSD&Code2=1217030&Data=Count&SearchText=Sydney&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=12&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1\n |work        = 2011 Census\n |publisher   = Queen's Printer for Canada\n |access-date  = 2012-05-18\n |author      = Statistics Canada\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130207124555/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page_Map-Carte.cfm?Lang=E&Tab=3&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0913&Geo2=CSD&Code2=1217030&Data=Count&SearchText=Sydney&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=12&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1\n |archive-date = 7 February 2013\n |location    = Ottawa\n |year        = 2012b\n |ref         = harv\n |url-status    = live\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n*{{cite web\n | url = http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=5694&t=12&ln=Yazer\n | title = Jack Yazer, C.M., O.N.S., LL.D. Sydney, Nova Scotia, Canada\n | accessdate = 2015-10-04\n | year = 2000\n | publisher = Office of the Secretary to the Governor General\n | ref = {{harvid|Jack Yazer, C.M., O.N.S., LL.D. Sydney, Nova Scotia, Canada|(2000)}}\n | location = Halifax\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n{{Cape Breton Regional Municipality}}\n{{NSCapeBreton}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1785]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:1995 disestablishments in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Communities in the Cape Breton Regional Municipality]]\n[[Category:Former cities in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns on the Canadian Atlantic coast]]\n[[Category:General Service Areas in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Former colonial capitals in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "2601:248:5000:630:90e7:11be:7687:7bb8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGeography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sydney,_Nova_Scotia"}
{"title_page": "P. J. Patterson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= [[The Most Honourable]]\n|birthname=Percival Noel James Patterson\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Nation|ON]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] [[Queens Counsel|QC]]\n|image=PJPatterson.jpg\n|caption=Patterson in 2005\n|order1= 6th [[Prime Minister of Jamaica]]\n|term_start1    = 30 January 1992\n|term_end1      = 30 March 2006\n|monarch1           = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|governor_general1  = [[Howard Cooke|Sir Howard Cooke]]<br />[[Kenneth O. Hall|Sir Kenneth O. Hall]]\n|deputy1       = [[Seymour Mullings]] (1993-2002)\n|predecessor1  = [[Michael Manley]]\n|successor1    = [[Portia Simpson-Miller]]\n|office2= [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Minister of Defence]]\n|term_start2    = 30 January 1992\n|term_end2      = 30 January 2005\n|predecessor2  = [[Michael Manley]]\n|successor2    = [[Portia Simpson-Miller]]\n|office3= [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Deputy Prime Minister of Jamaica]]\n|primeminister3= [[Michael Manley]]\n|term_start3    = February 1989\n|term_end3      = January 1992\n|primeminister4= [[Michael Manley]]\n|term_start4    = 1978\n|term_end4      = 1980\n|office5        = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade (Jamaica)|Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade]]\n|primeminister5= [[Michael Manley]]\n|predecessor5  = [[Dudley Thompson]]\n|successor5    = [[Hugh Shearer]]\n|term_start5   = 1978\n|term_end5     = 1980\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1935|4|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Hanover, Jamaica|Hanover]], [[British Jamaica|Jamaica]], [[Colony of Jamaica]]\n|nationality   = Jamaican \n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|spouse=\n|party= [[People's National Party]] <small>(1967\u2013present)}}\n\n'''Percival Noel James Patterson''', [[Order of the Nation|ON]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (born 10 April 1935), is a [[Jamaican people|Jamaican]] former politician who served as the sixth [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Prime Minister]] of [[Jamaica]] from 1992 to 2005. He was the leader of the [[People's National Party]] from 1992 to 2005, and the Member of Parliament (MP) for the constituency of Westmoreland South Eastern from 1970 to [[1980 Jamaican general election|1980]] (when he lost to Euphemia Williams of the [[Jamaica Labour Party]]) and again from 1989 to 1993. Following a constituency reorganization, he served as the MP for Westmoreland Eastern from 1993 to 2005. He retired from all of these positions in January 2005. He was married to [[Shirley Field-Ridley]] (d. 1982) with whom he had two children, Richard and Sharon.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/28/obituaries/shirley-field-ridley-45-held-posts-in-the-guyana-cabinet.html \"Shirley Field-Ridley, 45, Held Posts in the Guyana Cabinet\" (obituary)], ''New York Times'', 28 June 1982.</ref>\n\nCabinet positions he held during his political career include Minister of Industry and Tourism; Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade; Minister of Development, Planning and Production; Minister of Finance and Planning.<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/westernnews/33474_Profile-on-PJ-Patterson \"Profile on PJ Patterson\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210904/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/westernnews/33474_Profile-on-PJ-Patterson |date=29 October 2013}}, ''Jamaica Observer'', 12 October 2002.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nP.J.'s parents were Henry Patterson, a farmer, and Ina James, a primary school teacher, who both hailed from the [[Hanover Parish]] in western [[Jamaica]]. Patterson received his secondary education at one of Jamaica's most prominent learning institutions, [[Calabar High School]], before moving on to pursue higher studies at the [[University of the West Indies|University College of West Indies]] and later the [[London School of Economics]].<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWhile pursuing his bachelor's degree in English at the [[University of the West Indies]], he served as Chairman of the university's External Affairs Commission, where he gained exposure to world leaders and international political thought through attendance at a number of international student fora. It was also at university that he developed a commitment to [[Caribbean#Regionalism|Caribbean regionalism]] as well as to the causes of the countries of the developing world. In 1958, he graduated with a B.A. (Honours).<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nHis time as a Law student of the [[London School of Economics]] consolidated the foundation in international politics that his university experience in Jamaica had provided. He was awarded the Leverhume Scholarship, and the Sir Hughes Parry prize for Excellence in the Law of Contracts.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring his enrolment at the [[Inns of Court]] (Middle Temple) he again came in contact with a number of future leaders of the countries of the developing world who were fellow students in England.\n\n==Early political life==\nPatterson joined the organising staff of the [[People's National Party]] in 1958, and he became a member of the party's National and Executive Councils in 1964. Patterson entered the [[Parliament of Jamaica]] as an Opposition Senator in 1969, appointed by Opposition Leader [[Norman Manley]]. He was elected the youngest ever Vice President of the [[People's National Party]] later that year at age 33.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWhen in 1969 his predecessor as Prime Minister of Jamaica, [[Michael Manley]], launched his campaign for the Presidency of the PNP, he turned to P. J. Patterson, youngest of the highest-ranking segment of the party executive, to lead his campaign. This was the beginning of a partnership which endured over the next 23 years, and allowed for an exchange of political ideas and perspectives that proved beneficial to both.\n\nPatterson was elected the Member of Parliament for Westmoreland South Eastern in the constituency's by-election of 1970. The constituency borders were reorganized prior to the [[1993 Jamaican general election|general election of 1993]] and he was elected as the Member of Parliament for Westmoreland Eastern in that election, a seat he held until his retirement in 2006.\n\nHe was Campaign Manager for the [[Peoples National Party|People's National Party]]'s bid for power in the General Elections of 1972, demonstrating skill as a political organizer that played a significant role in the party's victory at the polls that year. This led to his first appointment to the Jamaican Cabinet as Minister of Industry, Trade and Tourism. From 1978-1980, Patterson served as deputy prime minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe PNP were voted out of power in 1980, and Patterson lost his seat to Euphemia Williams. However, in 1983, he was elected party chairman, and the PNP won by a landslide in 1989, and Patterson was back as deputy prime minister. From 1989-1990, Patterson was also Minister of Development, Planning and Production, and from 1990-1, he was Minister of Finance and Planning.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Premiership==\nHe assumed office as Prime Minister after [[Michael Manley]] retired in 1992, at a time when the Caribbean island nation was facing the formidable challenge of securing a place in a new global order of economic [[liberalization]] and [[deregulation]]. In 1993, Patterson led the PNP to a second consecutive victory in the polls, winning 52 of the 60 seats up for grabs.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPatterson led efforts to strengthen the country's social protection and security systems\u2014a critical element of his economic and social policy agenda to mitigate, reduce poverty and social deprivation.<ref>Franklyn, Delano (ed.): 2002. ''The Challenges of Change: P. J. Patterson Budget Presentations 1992\u20132002''. Kingston, Jamaica: Ian Randle Publishers.</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Patterson led the PNP to a third consecutive victory, breaking the \"third-term barrier\". The PNP won 50 of the 60 seats available.\n\nHis massive investments in modernization of Jamaica's [[infrastructure]] and restructuring of the country's financial sector are widely credited with having led to Jamaica's greatest period of investment in tourism, mining, [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] and energy since the 1960s. He also ended Jamaica's 18-year borrowing relationship with the [[International Monetary Fund]],<ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/country/jam/index.htm Jamaica and the IMF.]</ref> allowing the country greater latitude in pursuit of its economic policies. In 2002, when Patterson led the PNP to another general election victory, but with a much-reduced majority of 34 out of 60 seats. He became the first Jamaican prime minister to be sworn in for a fourth consecutive term.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2003 Patterson told a party conference that he wanted Jamaica to be a [[republic]] by the time he left office in 2007, saying \"The majority of people in Jamaica are ready to consign to history the last vestiges of colonialism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3127742.stm|title=Jamaica eyes republican future|work=BBC News|date=2003-09-22|accessdate=2014-08-14}}</ref> Patterson had long supported moves to make Jamaica a republic, but he was unsuccessful in this aim, as Jamaica is still a monarchy. In 2012 he expressed his frustration that a republic had still not come into being<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailyherald.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25129:pj-patterson-unhappy-with-pace-of-change-&catid=2:news&Itemid=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814171652/http://www.thedailyherald.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25129:pj-patterson-unhappy-with-pace-of-change-&catid=2:news&Itemid=5|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-08-14|title=PJ Patterson unhappy with pace of change|newspaper=The Daily Herald|date=2012-02-09|accessdate=2014-08-14}}</ref>\n\nHe made international headlines in 2004 when, as Chairman of [[CARICOM]], he led the regional organization in the decision to refuse recognition of the [[G\u00e9rard Latortue]] government in Haiti following the removal of the democratically elected [[Jean-Bertrand Aristide]] from office. Patterson arranged for Aristide to take up temporary residence in Jamaica during Aristide's lawsuit against the United States and France accusing the countries of kidnapping him.\n\nIn one of his final initiatives as Prime Minister, he launched a program of radical transformation of the island's [[education]] system aimed at development of quality human capital equipped to succeed in the competitive [[globalization|global economy]].<ref>Franklyn, Delano (ed.), 2002. ''A Jamaican Voice in the Caribbean and World Politics: P. J. Patterson Selected Speeches 1992\u20132000''. Kingston, Jamaica: Ian Randle Publishers.</ref> In addition, Patterson presided over a significant decline in poverty during his time in office.<ref>Estanislao Gacit\u00faa-Mari\u00f3, Andrew Norton and Sophia V. Georgieva, ''Building Equality and Opportunity through Social Guarantees: new approaches to public policy and the realization of rights''.</ref>\n\nIn 2000-2004 murder rate in Jamaica increased from 32 to 58.\n\n==Post-premiership==\nFollowing his premiership, from 2006 to 2007, he chaired the [[Committee on Commonwealth Membership]], which presented its report<ref>[http://www.thecommonwealth.org/shared_asp_files/GFSR.asp?NodeID=174532 Report of the Committee on Commonwealth Membership, 2007 CHOGM.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426044116/http://www.thecommonwealth.org/shared_asp_files/GFSR.asp?NodeID=174532 |date=26 April 2009 }}</ref> on potential changes in [[Commonwealth of Nations membership criteria|membership criteria]] for the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] at the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2007]] in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].\n\n==International service==\nPatterson is a member of the Club de Madrid, a group that consists of more than 100 former Presidents and Prime Ministers of democratic countries, which works to strengthen democracy and democratic leadership worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clubmadrid.org/en/estructura/former_heads_of_state_and_government_1/letra:p |title=Club de Madrid website. |access-date=23 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923204848/http://www.clubmadrid.org/en/estructura/former_heads_of_state_and_government_1/letra:p |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nPatterson has contributed to numerous Conventions and Statements in the international arena including the Valletta Statement on Multilateral Trade and the Gozo Statement on Vulnerable Small States. These have helped to shape north-south relationship and influence the negotiating position of developing countries.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Global Leadership Foundation]], an [[NGO]] composed of a number of former statesmen, ex-presidents and Prime Ministers founded in 2004 by former State President of [[South Africa]] and [[Nobel Prize]] laureate [[F. W. de Klerk]].  The Global Leadership Foundation is an organization which works to support democratic leadership, prevent and resolve conflict through mediation and promote good governance in the form of democratic institutions, open markets, human rights and the rule of law. It does so by making available, discreetly and in confidence, the experience of former leaders to today's national leaders. It is a not-for-profit organization composed of former heads of government, senior governmental and international organization officials who work closely with Heads of Government on governance-related issues of concern to them.\n\nHe played a seminal role in the process that marked the transition from the first steps in integration of the Caribbean region to the founding of CARIFTA and its evolution into [[CARICOM]]. He drew upon his expertise in law and trade, to steer the regional body toward the development of a Caribbean jurisprudence through the [[Caribbean Court of Justice]], and a borderless regional economy through the [[CARICOM Single Market]], which came to fruition in 2005 and 2006 respectively.\n\nDuring his tenure as Jamaica's Foreign Minister he served as President of the [[African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States|ACP]]/[[European Union|EU]] Ministerial Council and led negotiations for the [[African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States|ACP]] group of countries with the European Community. As Chairman of the ACP/EEC Ministerial Conference, he played a pivotal role in forging an agreement on the basic framework for the original [[Lom\u00e9 Convention]], which influenced the outcome of subsequent negotiations that led to the Convention signed in 1975. He has served as President and Spokesman of the ACP Ministerial Council on a number of occasions.\n\nA passionate opponent of [[apartheid]], he was an ardent proponent of [[South Africa]]'s liberation movement.\n\n==Memberships and awards==\nUpon becoming the Prime Minister of Jamaica in 1992 Patterson was invested with the [[Order of the Nation]], allowing him to be known as \"The Most Honourable\" and to use the post-nominal letters \"ON\".\n\nIn 2006 he was invested with the [[Order of Excellence of Guyana]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20070807150647/http://www.op.gov.gy/stories/060529.html] allowing him to use the post-nominal letters \"OE\". [http://medals.org.uk/guyana/guyana001.htm]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the [[People's National Party]]|before=[[Michael Manley]]|after=[[Portia Simpson-Miller]]| years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Jamaica]]|before=[[Michael Manley]]|after=[[Portia Simpson-Miller]]| years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{JamaicaPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patterson, P. J.}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:University of the West Indies alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Jamaican lawyers]]\n[[Category:Jamaican republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Hanover Parish]]\n[[Category:People's National Party (Jamaica) politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Companions of O. R. Tambo]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Excellence of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Nation]]\n[[Category:Jamaican Queen's Counsel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= [[The Most Honourable]]\n|birthname=Percival Noel James Patterson\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Nation|ON]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] [[Queens Counsel|QC]]\n|image=PJPatterson.jpg\n|caption=Patterson in 2005\n|order1= 6th [[Prime Minister of Jamaica]]\n|term_start1    = 30 January 1992\n|term_end1      = 30 January 2005\n|monarch1           = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|governor_general1  = [[Howard Cooke|Sir Howard Cooke]]<br />[[Kenneth O. Hall|Sir Kenneth O. Hall]]\n|deputy1       = [[Seymour Mullings]] (1993-2002)\n|predecessor1  = [[Michael Manley]]\n|successor1    = [[Portia Simpson-Miller]]\n|office2= [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Minister of Defence]]\n|term_start2    = 30 January 1992\n|term_end2      = 30 January 2005\n|predecessor2  = [[Michael Manley]]\n|successor2    = [[Portia Simpson-Miller]]\n|office3= [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Deputy Prime Minister of Jamaica]]\n|primeminister3= [[Michael Manley]]\n|term_start3    = February 1989\n|term_end3      = January 1992\n|primeminister4= [[Michael Manley]]\n|term_start4    = 1978\n|term_end4      = 1980\n|office5        = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade (Jamaica)|Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade]]\n|primeminister5= [[Michael Manley]]\n|predecessor5  = [[Dudley Thompson]]\n|successor5    = [[Hugh Shearer]]\n|term_start5   = 1978\n|term_end5     = 1980\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1935|4|10|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Hanover, Jamaica|Hanover]], [[British Jamaica|Jamaica]], [[Colony of Jamaica]]\n|nationality   = Jamaican \n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|spouse=\n|party= [[People's National Party]] <small>(1967\u2013present)}}\n\n'''Percival Noel James Patterson''', [[Order of the Nation|ON]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (born 10 April 1935), is a [[Jamaican people|Jamaican]] former politician who served as the sixth [[Prime Minister of Jamaica|Prime Minister]] of [[Jamaica]] from 1992 to 2005. He was the leader of the [[People's National Party]] from 1992 to 2005, and the Member of Parliament (MP) for the constituency of Westmoreland South Eastern from 1970 to [[1980 Jamaican general election|1980]] (when he lost to Euphemia Williams of the [[Jamaica Labour Party]]) and again from 1989 to 1993. Following a constituency reorganization, he served as the MP for Westmoreland Eastern from 1993 to 2005. He retired from all of these positions in January 2005. He was married to [[Shirley Field-Ridley]] (d. 1982) with whom he had two children, Richard and Sharon.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/28/obituaries/shirley-field-ridley-45-held-posts-in-the-guyana-cabinet.html \"Shirley Field-Ridley, 45, Held Posts in the Guyana Cabinet\" (obituary)], ''New York Times'', 28 June 1982.</ref>\n\nCabinet positions he held during his political career include Minister of Industry and Tourism; Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade; Minister of Development, Planning and Production; Minister of Finance and Planning.<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/westernnews/33474_Profile-on-PJ-Patterson \"Profile on PJ Patterson\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210904/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/westernnews/33474_Profile-on-PJ-Patterson |date=29 October 2013}}, ''Jamaica Observer'', 12 October 2002.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nP.J.'s parents were Henry Patterson, a farmer, and Ina James, a primary school teacher, who both hailed from the [[Hanover Parish]] in western [[Jamaica]]. Patterson received his secondary education at one of Jamaica's most prominent learning institutions, [[Calabar High School]], before moving on to pursue higher studies at the [[University of the West Indies|University College of West Indies]] and later the [[London School of Economics]].<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWhile pursuing his bachelor's degree in English at the [[University of the West Indies]], he served as Chairman of the university's External Affairs Commission, where he gained exposure to world leaders and international political thought through attendance at a number of international student fora. It was also at university that he developed a commitment to [[Caribbean#Regionalism|Caribbean regionalism]] as well as to the causes of the countries of the developing world. In 1958, he graduated with a B.A. (Honours).<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nHis time as a Law student of the [[London School of Economics]] consolidated the foundation in international politics that his university experience in Jamaica had provided. He was awarded the Leverhume Scholarship, and the Sir Hughes Parry prize for Excellence in the Law of Contracts.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring his enrolment at the [[Inns of Court]] (Middle Temple) he again came in contact with a number of future leaders of the countries of the developing world who were fellow students in England.\n\n==Early political life==\nPatterson joined the organising staff of the [[People's National Party]] in 1958, and he became a member of the party's National and Executive Councils in 1964. Patterson entered the [[Parliament of Jamaica]] as an Opposition Senator in 1969, appointed by Opposition Leader [[Norman Manley]]. He was elected the youngest ever Vice President of the [[People's National Party]] later that year at age 33.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWhen in 1969 his predecessor as Prime Minister of Jamaica, [[Michael Manley]], launched his campaign for the Presidency of the PNP, he turned to P. J. Patterson, youngest of the highest-ranking segment of the party executive, to lead his campaign. This was the beginning of a partnership which endured over the next 23 years, and allowed for an exchange of political ideas and perspectives that proved beneficial to both.\n\nPatterson was elected the Member of Parliament for Westmoreland South Eastern in the constituency's by-election of 1970. The constituency borders were reorganized prior to the [[1993 Jamaican general election|general election of 1993]] and he was elected as the Member of Parliament for Westmoreland Eastern in that election, a seat he held until his retirement in 2006.\n\nHe was Campaign Manager for the [[Peoples National Party|People's National Party]]'s bid for power in the General Elections of 1972, demonstrating skill as a political organizer that played a significant role in the party's victory at the polls that year. This led to his first appointment to the Jamaican Cabinet as Minister of Industry, Trade and Tourism. From 1978-1980, Patterson served as deputy prime minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs and Foreign Trade.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe PNP were voted out of power in 1980, and Patterson lost his seat to Euphemia Williams. However, in 1983, he was elected party chairman, and the PNP won by a landslide in 1989, and Patterson was back as deputy prime minister. From 1989-1990, Patterson was also Minister of Development, Planning and Production, and from 1990-1, he was Minister of Finance and Planning.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\n==Premiership==\nHe assumed office as Prime Minister after [[Michael Manley]] retired in 1992, at a time when the Caribbean island nation was facing the formidable challenge of securing a place in a new global order of economic [[liberalization]] and [[deregulation]]. In 1993, Patterson led the PNP to a second consecutive victory in the polls, winning 52 of the 60 seats up for grabs.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPatterson led efforts to strengthen the country's social protection and security systems\u2014a critical element of his economic and social policy agenda to mitigate, reduce poverty and social deprivation.<ref>Franklyn, Delano (ed.): 2002. ''The Challenges of Change: P. J. Patterson Budget Presentations 1992\u20132002''. Kingston, Jamaica: Ian Randle Publishers.</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Patterson led the PNP to a third consecutive victory, breaking the \"third-term barrier\". The PNP won 50 of the 60 seats available.\n\nHis massive investments in modernization of Jamaica's [[infrastructure]] and restructuring of the country's financial sector are widely credited with having led to Jamaica's greatest period of investment in tourism, mining, [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] and energy since the 1960s. He also ended Jamaica's 18-year borrowing relationship with the [[International Monetary Fund]],<ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/country/jam/index.htm Jamaica and the IMF.]</ref> allowing the country greater latitude in pursuit of its economic policies. In 2002, when Patterson led the PNP to another general election victory, but with a much-reduced majority of 34 out of 60 seats. He became the first Jamaican prime minister to be sworn in for a fourth consecutive term.<ref>https://nlj.gov.jm/biographies/rt-hon-percival-james-patterson-1935/ Retrieved 29 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2003 Patterson told a party conference that he wanted Jamaica to be a [[republic]] by the time he left office in 2007, saying \"The majority of people in Jamaica are ready to consign to history the last vestiges of colonialism\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3127742.stm|title=Jamaica eyes republican future|work=BBC News|date=2003-09-22|accessdate=2014-08-14}}</ref> Patterson had long supported moves to make Jamaica a republic, but he was unsuccessful in this aim, as Jamaica is still a monarchy. In 2012 he expressed his frustration that a republic had still not come into being<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailyherald.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25129:pj-patterson-unhappy-with-pace-of-change-&catid=2:news&Itemid=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814171652/http://www.thedailyherald.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=25129:pj-patterson-unhappy-with-pace-of-change-&catid=2:news&Itemid=5|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-08-14|title=PJ Patterson unhappy with pace of change|newspaper=The Daily Herald|date=2012-02-09|accessdate=2014-08-14}}</ref>\n\nHe made international headlines in 2004 when, as Chairman of [[CARICOM]], he led the regional organization in the decision to refuse recognition of the [[G\u00e9rard Latortue]] government in Haiti following the removal of the democratically elected [[Jean-Bertrand Aristide]] from office. Patterson arranged for Aristide to take up temporary residence in Jamaica during Aristide's lawsuit against the United States and France accusing the countries of kidnapping him.\n\nIn one of his final initiatives as Prime Minister, he launched a program of radical transformation of the island's [[education]] system aimed at development of quality human capital equipped to succeed in the competitive [[globalization|global economy]].<ref>Franklyn, Delano (ed.), 2002. ''A Jamaican Voice in the Caribbean and World Politics: P. J. Patterson Selected Speeches 1992\u20132000''. Kingston, Jamaica: Ian Randle Publishers.</ref> In addition, Patterson presided over a significant decline in poverty during his time in office.<ref>Estanislao Gacit\u00faa-Mari\u00f3, Andrew Norton and Sophia V. Georgieva, ''Building Equality and Opportunity through Social Guarantees: new approaches to public policy and the realization of rights''.</ref>\n\nIn 2000-2004 murder rate in Jamaica increased from 32 to 58.\n\n==Post-premiership==\nFollowing his premiership, from 2006 to 2007, he chaired the [[Committee on Commonwealth Membership]], which presented its report<ref>[http://www.thecommonwealth.org/shared_asp_files/GFSR.asp?NodeID=174532 Report of the Committee on Commonwealth Membership, 2007 CHOGM.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090426044116/http://www.thecommonwealth.org/shared_asp_files/GFSR.asp?NodeID=174532 |date=26 April 2009 }}</ref> on potential changes in [[Commonwealth of Nations membership criteria|membership criteria]] for the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] at the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2007]] in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]].\n\n==International service==\nPatterson is a member of the Club de Madrid, a group that consists of more than 100 former Presidents and Prime Ministers of democratic countries, which works to strengthen democracy and democratic leadership worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.clubmadrid.org/en/estructura/former_heads_of_state_and_government_1/letra:p |title=Club de Madrid website. |access-date=23 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923204848/http://www.clubmadrid.org/en/estructura/former_heads_of_state_and_government_1/letra:p |archive-date=23 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nPatterson has contributed to numerous Conventions and Statements in the international arena including the Valletta Statement on Multilateral Trade and the Gozo Statement on Vulnerable Small States. These have helped to shape north-south relationship and influence the negotiating position of developing countries.\n\nHe is a member of the [[Global Leadership Foundation]], an [[NGO]] composed of a number of former statesmen, ex-presidents and Prime Ministers founded in 2004 by former State President of [[South Africa]] and [[Nobel Prize]] laureate [[F. W. de Klerk]].  The Global Leadership Foundation is an organization which works to support democratic leadership, prevent and resolve conflict through mediation and promote good governance in the form of democratic institutions, open markets, human rights and the rule of law. It does so by making available, discreetly and in confidence, the experience of former leaders to today's national leaders. It is a not-for-profit organization composed of former heads of government, senior governmental and international organization officials who work closely with Heads of Government on governance-related issues of concern to them.\n\nHe played a seminal role in the process that marked the transition from the first steps in integration of the Caribbean region to the founding of CARIFTA and its evolution into [[CARICOM]]. He drew upon his expertise in law and trade, to steer the regional body toward the development of a Caribbean jurisprudence through the [[Caribbean Court of Justice]], and a borderless regional economy through the [[CARICOM Single Market]], which came to fruition in 2005 and 2006 respectively.\n\nDuring his tenure as Jamaica's Foreign Minister he served as President of the [[African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States|ACP]]/[[European Union|EU]] Ministerial Council and led negotiations for the [[African, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States|ACP]] group of countries with the European Community. As Chairman of the ACP/EEC Ministerial Conference, he played a pivotal role in forging an agreement on the basic framework for the original [[Lom\u00e9 Convention]], which influenced the outcome of subsequent negotiations that led to the Convention signed in 1975. He has served as President and Spokesman of the ACP Ministerial Council on a number of occasions.\n\nA passionate opponent of [[apartheid]], he was an ardent proponent of [[South Africa]]'s liberation movement.\n\n==Memberships and awards==\nUpon becoming the Prime Minister of Jamaica in 1992 Patterson was invested with the [[Order of the Nation]], allowing him to be known as \"The Most Honourable\" and to use the post-nominal letters \"ON\".\n\nIn 2006 he was invested with the [[Order of Excellence of Guyana]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20070807150647/http://www.op.gov.gy/stories/060529.html] allowing him to use the post-nominal letters \"OE\". [http://medals.org.uk/guyana/guyana001.htm]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the [[People's National Party]]|before=[[Michael Manley]]|after=[[Portia Simpson-Miller]]| years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Prime Minister of Jamaica]]|before=[[Michael Manley]]|after=[[Portia Simpson-Miller]]| years=1992-2006}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{JamaicaPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patterson, P. J.}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:University of the West Indies alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Jamaican lawyers]]\n[[Category:Jamaican republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Hanover Parish]]\n[[Category:People's National Party (Jamaica) politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Companions of O. R. Tambo]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Excellence of Guyana]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Nation]]\n[[Category:Jamaican Queen's Counsel]]\n", "name_user": "NYC6x7x", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P._J._Patterson"}
{"title_page": "Henry Ainslie", "text_new": "{{short description|English physician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:Mrs Henry Ainslie with her child, by George Romney.jpg|thumb|Mrs Henry Ainslie with her child ([[George Romney (painter)|George Romney]])]]\n'''Henry Ainslie''' (21 March 1760 \u2013 1834) was a physician.  He was the son of the Kendal physician James Ainslie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.rcplondon.ac.uk/inspiring-physicians/henry-ainslie|title=Henry Ainslie|last=|first=|date=|website=Royal College of Physicians Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Educated at [[Hawkshead Grammar School]] and then [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]] (where he graduated [[Senior Wrangler]] and was second in the [[Smith Prize]]), he became a fellow of Pembroke in 1782, and a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] in 1795.<ref>{{acad|id=ANSY777H|name=Ainslie, Henry}}</ref><ref>Norman Moore, \u2018Ainslie, Henry (1760\u20131834)\u2019, rev. Patrick Wallis, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2008 http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/235, accessed 18 Sept 2008</ref> He was a Junior [[Commissioner for Madhouses]] in 1797 and 1798, and a Senior Commissioner in 1809 and 1817.  \n\nIn 1785 he married Agnes Ford of Monk Coniston (an estate near [[Coniston Water]] in the English [[English Lake District|Lake District]]) in the church at [[Colton, Cumbria|Colton]]. Agnes Ford was the daughter of Richard Ford, founder of the Newland Company, later known as [[Harrison Ainslie]].  The couple owned [[Grizedale Hall|Ford Lodge]] at [[Grizedale]] and planted many thousands of larch trees in the valley and on the surrounding hills and moorland which effectively started [[Grizedale Forest]]. They had a son [[Montague Ainslie]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/henry-ainslie-17601834-195511 Portrait of Henry Ainslie at Pembroke College]\n\n{{DNB Poster|Ainslie, Henry|Henry Ainslie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ainslie, Henry}}\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Senior Wranglers]]\n[[Category:1760 births]]\n[[Category:1834 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hawkshead Grammar School]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n\n\n{{England-med-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English physician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:Mrs Henry Ainslie with her child, by George Romney.jpg|thumb|Mrs Henry Ainslie with her child ([[George Romney (painter)|George Romney]])]]\n'''Henry Ainslie''' (21 March 1760 \u2013 1834) was a physician.  He was the son of the Kendal phsician James Ainslie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.rcplondon.ac.uk/inspiring-physicians/henry-ainslie|title=Henry Ainslie|last=|first=|date=|website=Royal College of Physicians Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Educated at [[Hawkshead Grammar School]] and then [[Pembroke College, Cambridge]] (where he graduated [[Senior Wrangler]] and was second in the [[Smith Prize]]), he became a fellow of Pembroke in 1782, and a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] in 1795.<ref>{{acad|id=ANSY777H|name=Ainslie, Henry}}</ref><ref>Norman Moore, \u2018Ainslie, Henry (1760\u20131834)\u2019, rev. Patrick Wallis, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2008 http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/235, accessed 18 Sept 2008</ref> He was a Junior [[Commissioner for Madhouses]] in 1797 and 1798, and a Senior Commissioner in 1809 and 1817.  \n\nIn 1785 he married Agnes Ford of Monk Coniston (an estate near [[Coniston Water]] in the English [[English Lake District|Lake District]]) in the church at [[Colton, Cumbria|Colton]]. Agnes Ford was the daughter of Richard Ford, founder of the Newland Company, later known as [[Harrison Ainslie]].  The couple owned [[Grizedale Hall|Ford Lodge]] at [[Grizedale]] and planted many thousands of larch trees in the valley and on the surrounding hills and moorland which effectively started [[Grizedale Forest]]. They had a son [[Montague Ainslie]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/henry-ainslie-17601834-195511 Portrait of Henry Ainslie at Pembroke College]\n\n{{DNB Poster|Ainslie, Henry|Henry Ainslie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ainslie, Henry}}\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Pembroke College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Senior Wranglers]]\n[[Category:1760 births]]\n[[Category:1834 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hawkshead Grammar School]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n\n\n{{England-med-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: phsician\u2192physician", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Ainslie"}
{"title_page": "Nai (caste)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Nai\n| population = \n| popplace = Almost all the states and union territories of India\n| languages = {{hlist|[[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]|[[Hindi]]|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|[[Kannada language|Kannada]]|[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]}}\n| rels = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\nThe '''Nai''' (also known as '''Nayee''', and as '''Valand''' in [[Gujarat]]) is a [[Caste system in India|caste]] originating in India.<ref name=PoIp1067>{{cite book |title=People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=XLII |editor1-first=A. |editor1-last=Hasan |editor2-first=J. C. |editor2-last=Das |page=1067}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1415\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Three edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 1415\u20131418</ref> The members were traditionally occupied as [[barber]]s, although some have adopted the name ''[[Sharma]]'' irrespectively to enhance their status.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sociology: A Study of the Social Sphere |first=Yogesh |last=Atal |publisher=Pearson Education India |isbn=978-8-13179-759-4 |page=242 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RuK9z3jLcwgC&pg=PA242}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nIn the state of [[Gujarat]], the Nais are referred by the name Valand. The Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the, [[Gohil]], and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ''ataks'', the main ones being the [[Parmar]] and Rathod. The Valand are [[endogamy|endogamous]] and practice clan [[exogamy]]. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas.<ref>{{cite book |title=People of India: Gujarat |volume=XXI, Part Three |editor1-first=R. B. |editor1-last=Lal |editor2-first=P. B. S. V. |editor2-last=Padmanabham |editor3-first=G. |editor3-last=Krishnan |editor4-first=M. Azeez |display-editors = 3 |editor4-last=Mohideen |pages=1415\u20131418}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2015}}{{Qn|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe Nai community is listed as an [[Other Backward Class]] in various regions of India. These include:\n*[[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/andhrapradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Assam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/assam.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Bihar]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/bihar.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Bihar |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Chandigarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/chandigarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Chhattisgarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/Chhattisgarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Dadra and Nagar Haveli]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/dadarandnagarhaveli.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Daman and Diu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/damananddiu.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Delhi]] [[National Capital Region (India)|NCR]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/delhi.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Delhi |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/goa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/gujarat.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Gujarat |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Haryana]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/haryana.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Haryana |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Himachal Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/himachalpradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\"/>\n*[[Jharkhand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/jharkhand.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Karnataka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/karnataka.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/madhyapradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Madhya Pradesh |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Maharashtra]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/maharashtra.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Maharashtra |page=4 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Odisha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/orrisa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Puducherry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/puducherry.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/punjab.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Punjab |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Rajasthan]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/rajasthan.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Rajasthan |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Tripura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tripura.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttarakhand|Uttaranchal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttaranchal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Uttar Pradesh |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[West Bengal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Clans and divisions of the Valand==\n\nThe Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the Soratia, Halai, Gohil, and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ataks, the main ones being the Solanki, Rathore,  Parmar and Padaliya . The Valand are endogamous and practice clan exogamy. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas. The community are still essentially involved in the barbering trade, with a few rural Valand have taken up agriculture. A few were practitioners of [[Ayurvedic]]  medicine.<ref name=\"autogenerated1415\"/>{{full citation needed|date=June 2016}}{{qn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nai}}\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Barber castes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Nai\n| population = \n| popplace = Almost all the states and union territories of India\n| languages = {{hlist|[[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]|[[Hindi]]|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]|[[Tamil language|Tamil]]|[[Kannada language|Kannada]]|[[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]|[[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]}}\n| rels = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\nThe '''Nai''' (also known as '''Nayee''', and as '''Valand''' in [[Gujarat]]) is a [[Caste system in India|caste]] originating in India.<ref name=PoIp1067>{{cite book |title=People of India: Uttar Pradesh |volume=XLII |editor1-first=A. |editor1-last=Hasan |editor2-first=J. C. |editor2-last=Das |page=1067}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1415\">People of India Gujarat Volume XXI  Part  Three edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 1415\u20131418</ref> The members were traditionally occupied as [[barber]]s, although some have adopted the name ''[[Sharma]]'' irrespectively to enhance their status.<ref>{{cite book |title=Sociology: A Study of the Social Sphere |first=Yogesh |last=Atal |publisher=Pearson Education India |isbn=978-8-13179-759-4 |page=242 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RuK9z3jLcwgC&pg=PA242}}</ref>\nTheir caste range from the [[Kshatriyas]] to [[Brahmins]] due to their main tradition. They are now known as the [[Kshatriyas]], but previously were regarded as the middle ([[Kshatriya]])due to their main tradition however now considered as a middle upper class caste.\nThis is why they were also previously regarded and in some parts of the world today as the [[Other backward class]] due to their previous tradition, but their caste community still remains in the middle high position, due to other traditions they did.\n\n==Distribution==\nIn the state of [[Gujarat]], the Nais are referred by the name Valand. The Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the, [[Gohil]], and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ''ataks'', the main ones being the [[Parmar]] and Rathod. The Valand are [[endogamy|endogamous]] and practice clan [[exogamy]]. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas.<ref>{{cite book |title=People of India: Gujarat |volume=XXI, Part Three |editor1-first=R. B. |editor1-last=Lal |editor2-first=P. B. S. V. |editor2-last=Padmanabham |editor3-first=G. |editor3-last=Krishnan |editor4-first=M. Azeez |display-editors = 3 |editor4-last=Mohideen |pages=1415\u20131418}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=January 2015}}{{Qn|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe Nai community is listed as an [[Other Backward Class]] in various regions of India. These include:\n*[[Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/andhrapradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Assam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/assam.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Bihar]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/bihar.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Bihar |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Chandigarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/chandigarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Chhattisgarh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/Chhattisgarh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Dadra and Nagar Haveli]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/dadarandnagarhaveli.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Daman and Diu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/damananddiu.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Delhi]] [[National Capital Region (India)|NCR]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/delhi.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Delhi |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/goa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Gujarat]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/gujarat.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Gujarat |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Haryana]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/haryana.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Haryana |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Himachal Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/himachalpradesh.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Goa]]<ref name=\"ncbc.nic.in\"/>\n*[[Jharkhand]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/jharkhand.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Karnataka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/karnataka.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Madhya Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/madhyapradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Madhya Pradesh |page=5 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Maharashtra]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/maharashtra.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Maharashtra |page=4 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Odisha]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/orrisa.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Puducherry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/puducherry.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Punjab, India|Punjab]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/punjab.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Punjab |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date= |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Rajasthan]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/rajasthan.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Rajasthan |page=2 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Tripura]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/tripura.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttarakhand|Uttaranchal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttaranchal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n*[[Uttar Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/uttarpradesh.pdf |title=Central List of OBCs for the State of Uttar Pradesh |page=3 |publisher=National Commission for Backward Classes |date=|accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n*[[West Bengal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbc.nic.in/Pdf/westbengal.pdf |title=National Commission for Backward Classes |publisher=Ncbc.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==Clans and divisions of the Valand==\n\nThe Valand have several territorial divisions, such as the Soratia, Halai, Gohil, and Jalawadi. They are further divided into clans, called ataks, the main ones being the Solanki, Rathore,  Parmar and Padaliya . The Valand are endogamous and practice clan exogamy. They speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and concentrated in the urban areas. The community are still essentially involved in the barbering trade, with a few rural Valand have taken up agriculture. A few were practitioners of [[Ayurvedic]]  medicine.<ref name=\"autogenerated1415\"/>{{full citation needed|date=June 2016}}{{qn|date=June 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nai}}\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Sikh communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Indian castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Assam]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Barber castes]]\n", "name_user": "PawanjiGupta", "label": "safe", "comment": "Unreferenced, caste promoted", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nai_(caste)"}
